# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fire-safe-polymers
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] An **acid** is a molecule or ion capable of either donating a proton (i.e. hydrogen cation, H+), known as a Brønsted–Lowry acid, or forming a covalent bond with an electron pair, known as a Lewis acid.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The first category of acids are the proton donors, or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] In the special case of aqueous solutions, proton donors form the hydronium ion H3O+ and are known as Arrhenius acids.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Brønsted and Lowry generalized the Arrhenius theory to include non-aqueous solvents.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] A Brønsted–Lowry or Arrhenius acid usually contains a hydrogen atom bonded to a chemical structure that is still energetically favorable after loss of H+.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Aqueous Arrhenius acids have characteristic properties that provide a practical description of an acid.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Acids form aqueous solutions with a sour taste, can turn blue litmus red, and react with bases and certain metals (like calcium) to form salts.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The word *acid* is derived from the Latin *acidus*, meaning 'sour'.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] An aqueous solution of an acid has a pH less than 7 and is colloquially also referred to as "acid" (as in "dissolved in acid"), while the strict definition refers only to the solute.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] A lower pH means a higher **acidity**, and thus a higher concentration of hydrogen cations in the solution.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Chemicals or substances having the property of an acid are said to be **acidic**.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] As these examples show, acids (in the colloquial sense) can be solutions or pure substances, and can be derived from acids (in the strict sense) that are solids, liquids, or gases.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Strong acids and some concentrated weak acids are corrosive, but there are exceptions such as carboranes and boric acid.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The second category of acids are Lewis acids, which form a covalent bond with an electron pair.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] An example is boron trifluoride (BF3), whose boron atom has a vacant orbital that can form a covalent bond by sharing a lone pair of electrons on an atom in a base, for example the nitrogen atom in ammonia (NH3).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Lewis considered this as a generalization of the Brønsted definition, so that an acid is a chemical species that accepts electron pairs either directly *or* by releasing protons (H+) into the solution, which then accept electron pairs.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Hydrogen chloride, acetic acid, and most other Brønsted–Lowry acids cannot form a covalent bond with an electron pair, however, and are therefore not Lewis acids.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Conversely, many Lewis acids are not Arrhenius or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] In modern terminology, an *acid* is implicitly a Brønsted acid and not a Lewis acid, since chemists almost always refer to a Lewis acid explicitly as such.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Modern definitions are concerned with the fundamental chemical reactions common to all acids.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Most acids encountered in everyday life are aqueous solutions, or can be dissolved in water, so the Arrhenius and Brønsted–Lowry definitions are the most relevant.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The Brønsted–Lowry definition is the most widely used definition; unless otherwise specified, acid–base reactions are assumed to involve the transfer of a proton (H+) from an acid to a base.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Hydronium ions are acids according to all three definitions.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Although alcohols and amines can be Brønsted–Lowry acids, they can also function as Lewis bases due to the lone pairs of electrons on their oxygen and nitrogen atoms.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] In 1884, Svante Arrhenius attributed the properties of acidity to hydrogen cations (H+), later described as protons or hydrons.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] An **Arrhenius acid** is a substance that, when added to water, increases the concentration of H+ ions in the water.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Chemists often write H+(*aq*) and refer to the hydrogen cation when describing acid–base reactions but the free hydrogen nucleus, a proton, does not exist alone in water, it exists as the **hydronium ion** (H3O+) or other forms (H5O2+, H9O4+).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Thus, an Arrhenius acid can also be described as a substance that increases the concentration of hydronium ions when added to water.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Examples include molecular substances such as hydrogen chloride and acetic acid.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] An Arrhenius base, on the other hand, is a substance that increases the concentration of hydroxide (OH−) ions when dissolved in water.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Due to this equilibrium, any increase in the concentration of hydronium is accompanied by a decrease in the concentration of hydroxide.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Thus, an Arrhenius acid could also be said to be one that decreases hydroxide concentration, while an Arrhenius base increases it.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] In an acidic solution, the concentration of hydronium ions is greater than 10−7 moles per liter.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Since pH is defined as the negative logarithm of the concentration of hydronium ions, acidic solutions thus have a pH of less than 7.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] While the Arrhenius concept is useful for describing many reactions, it is also quite limited in its scope.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] In 1923, chemists Johannes Nicolaus Brønsted and Thomas Martin Lowry independently recognized that acid–base reactions involve the transfer of a proton.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] A **Brønsted–Lowry acid** (or simply Brønsted acid) is a species that donates a proton to a Brønsted–Lowry base.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory has several advantages over Arrhenius theory.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Both theories easily describe the first reaction: CH3COOH acts as an Arrhenius acid because it acts as a source of H3O+ when dissolved in water, and it acts as a Brønsted acid by donating a proton to water.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] In the second example CH3COOH undergoes the same transformation, in this case donating a proton to ammonia (NH3), but does not relate to the Arrhenius definition of an acid because the reaction does not produce hydronium.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Nevertheless, CH3COOH is both an Arrhenius and a Brønsted–Lowry acid.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Brønsted–Lowry theory can be used to describe reactions of molecular compounds in nonaqueous solution or the gas phase.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Hydrogen chloride (HCl) and ammonia combine under several different conditions to form ammonium chloride, NH4Cl.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] In aqueous solution HCl behaves as hydrochloric acid and exists as hydronium and chloride ions.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] As with the acetic acid reactions, both definitions work for the first example, where water is the solvent and hydronium ion is formed by the HCl solute.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The next two reactions do not involve the formation of ions but are still proton-transfer reactions.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] In the second reaction hydrogen chloride and ammonia (dissolved in benzene) react to form solid ammonium chloride in a benzene solvent and in the third gaseous HCl and NH3 combine to form the solid.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] A third, only marginally related concept was proposed in 1923 by Gilbert N.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Lewis, which includes reactions with acid–base characteristics that do not involve a proton transfer.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] A **Lewis acid** is a species that accepts a pair of electrons from another species; in other words, it is an electron pair acceptor.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Brønsted acid–base reactions are proton transfer reactions while Lewis acid–base reactions are electron pair transfers.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Many Lewis acids are not Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] In the first reaction a fluoride ion, F−, gives up an electron pair to boron trifluoride to form the product tetrafluoroborate.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Fluoride "loses" a pair of valence electrons because the electrons shared in the B—F bond are located in the region of space between the two atomic nuclei and are therefore more distant from the fluoride nucleus than they are in the lone fluoride ion.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] BF3 is a Lewis acid because it accepts the electron pair from fluoride.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] This reaction cannot be described in terms of Brønsted theory because there is no proton transfer.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The second reaction can be described using either theory.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] A proton is transferred from an unspecified Brønsted acid to ammonia, a Brønsted base; alternatively, ammonia acts as a Lewis base and transfers a lone pair of electrons to form a bond with a hydrogen ion.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The species that gains the electron pair is the Lewis acid; for example, the oxygen atom in H3O+ gains a pair of electrons when one of the H—O bonds is broken and the electrons shared in the bond become localized on oxygen.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Depending on the context, a Lewis acid may also be described as an oxidizer or an electrophile.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Organic Brønsted acids, such as acetic, citric, or oxalic acid, are not Lewis acids.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] They dissociate in water to produce a Lewis acid, H+, but at the same time, they also yield an equal amount of a Lewis base (acetate, citrate, or oxalate, respectively, for the acids mentioned).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] This article deals mostly with Brønsted acids rather than Lewis acids.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Reactions of acids are often generalized in the form HA ⇌ H+ + A−, where HA represents the acid and A− is the conjugate base.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] This reaction is referred to as **protolysis**.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The protonated form (HA) of an acid is also sometimes referred to as the **free acid**.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Acid–base conjugate pairs differ by one proton, and can be interconverted by the addition or removal of a proton (protonation and deprotonation, respectively).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The acid can be the charged species and the conjugate base can be neutral in which case the generalized reaction scheme could be written as HA+ ⇌ H+ + A.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] In solution there exists an equilibrium between the acid and its conjugate base.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The equilibrium constant *K* is an expression of the equilibrium concentrations of the molecules or the ions in solution.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Brackets indicate concentration, such that [H2O] means *the concentration of H2O*.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The acid dissociation constant *K*a is generally used in the context of acid–base reactions.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The numerical value of *K*a is equal to the product (multiplication) of the concentrations of the products divided by the concentration of the reactants, where the reactant is the acid (HA) and the products are the conjugate base and H+.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The stronger of two acids will have a higher *K*a than the weaker acid; the ratio of hydrogen cations to acid will be higher for the stronger acid as the stronger acid has a greater tendency to lose its proton.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Because the range of possible values for *K*a spans many orders of magnitude, a more manageable constant, p*K*a is more frequently used, where p*K*a = −log10 *K*a.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Stronger acids have a smaller p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Experimentally determined p*K*a at 25 °C in aqueous solution are often quoted in textbooks and reference material.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Arrhenius acids are named according to their anions.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] In the classical naming system, the ionic suffix is dropped and replaced with a new suffix, according to the table following.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The prefix "hydro-" is used when the acid is made up of just hydrogen and one other element.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] For example, HCl has chloride as its anion, so the hydro- prefix is used, and the -ide suffix makes the name take the form hydrochloric acid.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] In the IUPAC naming system, "aqueous" is simply added to the name of the ionic compound.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Thus, for hydrogen chloride, as an acid solution, the IUPAC name is aqueous hydrogen chloride.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The strength of an acid refers to its ability or tendency to lose a proton.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] A strong acid is one that completely dissociates in water; in other words, one mole of a strong acid HA dissolves in water yielding one mole of H+ and one mole of the conjugate base, A−, and none of the protonated acid HA.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] In contrast, a weak acid only partially dissociates and at equilibrium both the acid and the conjugate base are in solution.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Examples of strong acids are hydrochloric acid (HCl), hydroiodic acid (HI), hydrobromic acid (HBr), perchloric acid (HClO4), nitric acid (HNO3) and sulfuric acid (H2SO4).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] In water, each of these essentially ionizes 100%.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The stronger an acid is, the more easily it loses a proton, H+.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Two key factors that contribute to the ease of deprotonation are the polarity of the H—A bond and the size of atom A, which determines the strength of the H—A bond.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Acid strengths are also often discussed in terms of the stability of the conjugate base.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Stronger acids have a larger acid dissociation constant, *K*a and a lower p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Sulfonic acids, which are organic oxyacids, are a class of strong acids.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] A common example is toluenesulfonic acid (tosylic acid).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Unlike sulfuric acid itself, sulfonic acids can be solids.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] In fact, polystyrene functionalized into polystyrene sulfonate is a solid strongly acidic plastic that is filterable.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Superacids are acids stronger than 100% sulfuric acid.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Examples of superacids are fluoroantimonic acid, magic acid and perchloric acid.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The strongest known acid is helium hydride ion, with a proton affinity of 177.8kJ/mol.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Superacids can permanently protonate water to give ionic, crystalline hydronium "salts".
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] They can also quantitatively stabilize carbocations.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] While *K*a measures the strength of an acid compound, the strength of an aqueous acid solution is measured by pH, which is an indication of the concentration of hydronium in the solution.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The pH of a simple solution of an acid compound in water is determined by the dilution of the compound and the compound's *K*a.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Lewis acids have been classified in the ECW model and it has been shown that there is no one order of acid strengths.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The relative acceptor strength of Lewis acids toward a series of bases, versus other Lewis acids, can be illustrated by C-B plots.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] It has been shown that to define the order of Lewis acid strength at least two properties must be considered.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] For Pearson's qualitative HSAB theory the two properties are hardness and strength while for Drago's quantitative ECW model the two properties are electrostatic and covalent.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Common examples of monoprotic acids in mineral acids include hydrochloric acid (HCl) and nitric acid (HNO3).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] On the other hand, for organic acids the term mainly indicates the presence of one carboxylic acid group and sometimes these acids are known as monocarboxylic acid.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Examples in organic acids include formic acid (HCOOH), acetic acid (CH3COOH) and benzoic acid (C6H5COOH).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Polyprotic acids, also known as polybasic acids, are able to donate more than one proton per acid molecule, in contrast to monoprotic acids that only donate one proton per molecule.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Specific types of polyprotic acids have more specific names, such as diprotic (or dibasic) acid (two potential protons to donate), and triprotic (or tribasic) acid (three potential protons to donate).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Some macromolecules such as proteins and nucleic acids can have a very large number of acidic protons.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] A diprotic acid (here symbolized by H2A) can undergo one or two dissociations depending on the pH.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Each dissociation has its own dissociation constant, Ka1 and Ka2.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The first dissociation constant is typically greater than the second (i.e., *K*a1 > *K*a2).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] For example, sulfuric acid (H2SO4) can donate one proton to form the bisulfate anion (HSO− 4), for which *K*a1 is very large; then it can donate a second proton to form the sulfate anion (SO2− 4), wherein the *K*a2 is intermediate strength.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The large *K*a1 for the first dissociation makes sulfuric a strong acid.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] In a similar manner, the weak unstable carbonic acid (H2CO3) can lose one proton to form bicarbonate anion (HCO− 3) and lose a second to form carbonate anion (CO2− 3).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Both *K*a values are small, but *K*a1 > *K*a2 .
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] A triprotic acid (H3A) can undergo one, two, or three dissociations and has three dissociation constants, where *K*a1 > *K*a2 > *K*a3.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] An inorganic example of a triprotic acid is orthophosphoric acid (H3PO4), usually just called phosphoric acid.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] All three protons can be successively lost to yield H2PO− 4, then HPO2− 4, and finally PO3− 4, the orthophosphate ion, usually just called phosphate.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Even though the positions of the three protons on the original phosphoric acid molecule are equivalent, the successive *K*a values differ since it is energetically less favorable to lose a proton if the conjugate base is more negatively charged.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] An organic example of a triprotic acid is citric acid, which can successively lose three protons to finally form the citrate ion.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Although the subsequent loss of each hydrogen ion is less favorable, all of the conjugate bases are present in solution.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The fractional concentration, *α* (alpha), for each species can be calculated.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] For example, a generic diprotic acid will generate 3 species in solution: H2A, HA−, and A2−.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] A plot of these fractional concentrations against pH, for given *K*1 and *K*2, is known as a Bjerrum plot.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] where *K*0 = 1 and the other K-terms are the dissociation constants for the acid.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Neutralization is the basis of titration, where a pH indicator shows equivalence point when the equivalent number of moles of a base have been added to an acid.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] It is often wrongly assumed that neutralization should result in a solution with pH 7.0, which is only the case with similar acid and base strengths during a reaction.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Neutralization with a base weaker than the acid results in a weakly acidic salt.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] An example is the weakly acidic ammonium chloride, which is produced from the strong acid hydrogen chloride and the weak base ammonia.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Conversely, neutralizing a weak acid with a strong base gives a weakly basic salt (e.g., sodium fluoride from hydrogen fluoride and sodium hydroxide).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] In order for a protonated acid to lose a proton, the pH of the system must rise above the p*K*a of the acid.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The decreased concentration of H+ in that basic solution shifts the equilibrium towards the conjugate base form (the deprotonated form of the acid).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] In lower-pH (more acidic) solutions, there is a high enough H+ concentration in the solution to cause the acid to remain in its protonated form.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Solutions of weak acids and salts of their conjugate bases form buffer solutions.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] To determine the concentration of an acid in an aqueous solution, an acid–base titration is commonly performed.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] A strong base solution with a known concentration, usually NaOH or KOH, is added to neutralize the acid solution according to the color change of the indicator with the amount of base added.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The titration curve of an acid titrated by a base has two axes, with the base volume on the x-axis and the solution's pH value on the y-axis.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The pH of the solution always goes up as the base is added to the solution.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] For each diprotic acid titration curve, from left to right, there are two midpoints, two equivalence points, and two buffer regions.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Due to the successive dissociation processes, there are two equivalence points in the titration curve of a diprotic acid.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The first equivalence point occurs when all first protons from the first ionization are titrated.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] In other words, the amount of OH− added equals the original amount of H2A at the first equivalence point.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The second equivalence point occurs when all protons are titrated.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Therefore, the amount of OH− added equals twice the amount of H2A at this time.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] For a weak diprotic acid titrated by a strong base, the second equivalence point must occur at pH above 7 due to the hydrolysis of the resulted salts in the solution.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] At either equivalence point, adding a drop of base will cause the steepest rise of the pH value in the system.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] A titration curve for a diprotic acid contains two midpoints where pH=pKa.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Since there are two different Ka values, the first midpoint occurs at pH=pKa1 and the second one occurs at pH=pKa2.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Each segment of the curve that contains a midpoint at its center is called the buffer region.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Because the buffer regions consist of the acid and its conjugate base, it can resist pH changes when base is added until the next equivalent points.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Acids are fundamental reagents in treating almost all processes in modern industry.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Sulfuric acid, a diprotic acid, is the most widely used acid in industry, and is also the most-produced industrial chemical in the world.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] It is mainly used in producing fertilizer, detergent, batteries and dyes, as well as used in processing many products such like removing impurities.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] According to the statistics data in 2011, the annual production of sulfuric acid was around 200 million tonnes in the world.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] For example, phosphate minerals react with sulfuric acid to produce phosphoric acid for the production of phosphate fertilizers, and zinc is produced by dissolving zinc oxide into sulfuric acid, purifying the solution and electrowinning.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] In the chemical industry, acids react in neutralization reactions to produce salts.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] For example, nitric acid reacts with ammonia to produce ammonium nitrate, a fertilizer.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Additionally, carboxylic acids can be esterified with alcohols, to produce esters.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Acids are often used to remove rust and other corrosion from metals in a process known as pickling.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] They may be used as an electrolyte in a wet cell battery, such as sulfuric acid in a car battery.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Tartaric acid is an important component of some commonly used foods like unripe mangoes and tamarind.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Natural fruits and vegetables also contain acids.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Citric acid is present in oranges, lemon and other citrus fruits.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Oxalic acid is present in tomatoes, spinach, and especially in carambola and rhubarb; rhubarb leaves and unripe carambolas are toxic because of high concentrations of oxalic acid.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Ascorbic acid (Vitamin C) is an essential vitamin for the human body and is present in such foods as amla (Indian gooseberry), lemon, citrus fruits, and guava.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Many acids can be found in various kinds of food as additives, as they alter their taste and serve as preservatives.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Phosphoric acid, for example, is a component of cola drinks.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Acetic acid is used in day-to-day life as vinegar.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Citric acid is used as a preservative in sauces and pickles.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Carbonic acid is one of the most common acid additives that are widely added in soft drinks.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] During the manufacturing process, CO2 is usually pressurized to dissolve in these drinks to generate carbonic acid.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Carbonic acid is very unstable and tends to decompose into water and CO2 at room temperature and pressure.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Therefore, when bottles or cans of these kinds of soft drinks are opened, the soft drinks fizz and effervesce as CO2 bubbles come out.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Acetylsalicylic acid (Aspirin) is used as a pain killer and for bringing down fevers.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Acids play important roles in the human body.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The hydrochloric acid present in the stomach aids digestion by breaking down large and complex food molecules.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Amino acids are required for synthesis of proteins required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Fatty acids are also required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Nucleic acids are important for the manufacturing of DNA and RNA and transmitting of traits to offspring through genes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Carbonic acid is important for maintenance of pH equilibrium in the body.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Human bodies contain a variety of organic and inorganic compounds, among those dicarboxylic acids play an essential role in many biological behaviors.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Many of those acids are amino acids, which mainly serve as materials for the synthesis of proteins.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Other weak acids serve as buffers with their conjugate bases to keep the body's pH from undergoing large scale changes that would be harmful to cells.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The rest of the dicarboxylic acids also participate in the synthesis of various biologically important compounds in human bodies.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Acids are used as catalysts in industrial and organic chemistry; for example, sulfuric acid is used in very large quantities in the alkylation process to produce gasoline.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Some acids, such as sulfuric, phosphoric, and hydrochloric acids, also effect dehydration and condensation reactions.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] In biochemistry, many enzymes employ acid catalysis.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Many biologically important molecules are acids.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Nucleic acids, which contain acidic phosphate groups, include DNA and RNA.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Nucleic acids contain the genetic code that determines many of an organism's characteristics, and is passed from parents to offspring.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] DNA contains the chemical blueprint for the synthesis of proteins, which are made up of amino acid subunits.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Cell membranes contain fatty acid esters such as phospholipids.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] An α-amino acid has a central carbon (the α or *alpha* carbon) that is covalently bonded to a carboxyl group (thus they are carboxylic acids), an amino group, a hydrogen atom and a variable group.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The variable group, also called the R group or side chain, determines the identity and many of the properties of a specific amino acid.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] In glycine, the simplest amino acid, the R group is a hydrogen atom, but in all other amino acids it is contains one or more carbon atoms bonded to hydrogens, and may contain other elements such as sulfur, oxygen or nitrogen.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] With the exception of glycine, naturally occurring amino acids are chiral and almost invariably occur in the L-configuration.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Peptidoglycan, found in some bacterial cell walls contains some D-amino acids.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] At physiological pH, typically around 7, free amino acids exist in a charged form, where the acidic carboxyl group (-COOH) loses a proton (-COO−) and the basic amine group (-NH2) gains a proton (-NH+ 3).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The entire molecule has a net neutral charge and is a zwitterion, with the exception of amino acids with basic or acidic side chains.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Aspartic acid, for example, possesses one protonated amine and two deprotonated carboxyl groups, for a net charge of −1 at physiological pH.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Fatty acids and fatty acid derivatives are another group of carboxylic acids that play a significant role in biology.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] These contain long hydrocarbon chains and a carboxylic acid group on one end.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The cell membrane of nearly all organisms is primarily made up of a phospholipid bilayer, a micelle of hydrophobic fatty acid esters with polar, hydrophilic phosphate "head" groups.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Membranes contain additional components, some of which can participate in acid–base reactions.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] In humans and many other animals, hydrochloric acid is a part of the gastric acid secreted within the stomach to help hydrolyze proteins and polysaccharides, as well as converting the inactive pro-enzyme, pepsinogen into the enzyme, pepsin.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Some organisms produce acids for defense; for example, ants produce formic acid.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Acid–base equilibrium plays a critical role in regulating mammalian breathing.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Oxygen gas (O2) drives cellular respiration, the process by which animals release the chemical potential energy stored in food, producing carbon dioxide (CO2) as a byproduct.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Oxygen and carbon dioxide are exchanged in the lungs, and the body responds to changing energy demands by adjusting the rate of ventilation.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] For example, during periods of exertion the body rapidly breaks down stored carbohydrates and fat, releasing CO2 into the blood stream.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] In aqueous solutions such as blood CO2 exists in equilibrium with carbonic acid and bicarbonate ion.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] It is the decrease in pH that signals the brain to breathe faster and deeper, expelling the excess CO2 and resupplying the cells with O2.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Cell membranes are generally impermeable to charged or large, polar molecules because of the lipophilic fatty acyl chains comprising their interior.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Many biologically important molecules, including a number of pharmaceutical agents, are organic weak acids that can cross the membrane in their protonated, uncharged form but not in their charged form (i.e., as the conjugate base).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] For this reason the activity of many drugs can be enhanced or inhibited by the use of antacids or acidic foods.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The charged form, however, is often more soluble in blood and cytosol, both aqueous environments.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] When the extracellular environment is more acidic than the neutral pH within the cell, certain acids will exist in their neutral form and will be membrane soluble, allowing them to cross the phospholipid bilayer.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Acids that lose a proton at the intracellular pH will exist in their soluble, charged form and are thus able to diffuse through the cytosol to their target.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Ibuprofen, aspirin and penicillin are examples of drugs that are weak acids.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] A sulfonic acid has the general formula RS(=O)2–OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] A carboxylic acid has the general formula R-C(O)OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] The carboxyl group -C(O)OH contains a carbonyl group, C=O, and a hydroxyl group, O-H.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Halogenation at alpha position increases acid strength, so that the following acids are all stronger than acetic acid.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] Normal carboxylic acids are the direct union of a carbonyl group and a hydroxyl group.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/acids] In vinylogous carboxylic acids, a carbon-carbon double bond separates the carbonyl and hydroxyl groups.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The use of adhesives offers certain advantages over other binding techniques such as sewing, mechanical fastenings, and welding.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] These include the ability to bind different materials together, the more efficient distribution of stress across a joint, the cost-effectiveness of an easily mechanized process, and greater flexibility in design.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Disadvantages of adhesive use include decreased stability at high temperatures, relative weakness in bonding large objects with a small bonding surface area, and greater difficulty in separating objects during testing.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Adhesives are typically organized by the method of adhesion followed by *reactive* or *non-reactive*, a term which refers to whether the adhesive chemically reacts in order to harden.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Alternatively, they can be organized either by their starting physical phase or whether their raw stock is of natural or synthetic origin.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Adhesives may be found naturally or produced synthetically.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The earliest known human use of adhesive-like substances was approximately 200,000 years ago, when Neanderthals produced tar from the dry distillation of birch bark for use in binding stone tools to wooden handles.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The first references to adhesives in literature appeared approximately 2000 BC.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The Greeks and Romans made great contributions to the development of adhesives.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] In Europe, glue was not widely used until the period AD 1500–1700.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] From then until the 1900s increases in adhesive use and discovery were relatively gradual.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Only since the 20th century has the development of synthetic adhesives accelerated rapidly, and innovation in the field continues to the present.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The earliest evidence of human adhesive use was discovered in central Italy when three stone implements were discovered with birch bark tar indications.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The tools were dated to about 200,000 before present in the Middle Paleolithic.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] It is the earliest example of tar-hafted stone tools.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] An experimental archeology study published in 2019 demonstrated how birch bark tar can be produced in an easier, more discoverable process.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] It involves directly burning birch bark under an overhanging rock surface in an open-air environment and collecting the tar that builds up on the rock.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Although sticky enough, plant-based, single-component adhesives can be brittle and vulnerable to environmental conditions.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The first use of compound adhesives was discovered in Sibudu, South Africa.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Here, 70,000-year-old stone segments that were once inserted in axe hafts were discovered covered with an adhesive composed of plant gum and red ochre (natural iron oxide) as adding ochre to plant gum produces a stronger product and protects the gum from disintegrating under wet conditions.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The ability to produce stronger adhesives allowed middle Stone Age humans to attach stone segments to sticks in greater variations, which led to the development of new tools.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] A study of material from Le Moustier indicates that Middle Paleolithic people, possibly Neanderthals, used glue made from a mixture of ocher and bitumen to make hand grips for cutting and scraping stone tools.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] More recent examples of adhesive use by prehistoric humans have been found at the burial sites of ancient tribes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Archaeologists studying the sites found that approximately 6,000 years ago the tribesmen had buried their dead together with food found in broken clay pots repaired with tree resins.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Another investigation by archaeologists uncovered the use of bituminous cements to fasten ivory eyeballs to statues in Babylonian temples dating to approximately 4000 BC.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] In 2000, a paper revealed the discovery of a 5,200-year-old man nicknamed the "Tyrolean Iceman" or "Ötzi", who was preserved in a glacier near the Austria-Italy border.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Several of his belongings were found with him including two arrows with flint arrowheads and a copper hatchet, each with evidence of organic glue used to connect the stone or metal parts to the wooden shafts.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The glue was analyzed as pitch, which requires the heating of tar during its production.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The retrieval of this tar requires a transformation of birch bark by means of heat, in a process known as pyrolysis.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The first references to adhesives in literature appeared in approximately 2000 BC.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Further historical records of adhesive use are found from the period spanning 1500–1000 BC.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Artifacts from this period include paintings depicting wood gluing operations and a casket made of wood and glue in King Tutankhamun's tomb.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Other ancient Egyptian artifacts employ animal glue for bonding or lamination.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Such lamination of wood for bows and furniture is thought to have extended their life and was accomplished using casein (milk protein)-based glues.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The ancient Egyptians also developed starch-based pastes for the bonding of papyrus to clothing and a plaster of Paris-like material made of calcined gypsum.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] From AD 1 to 500 the Greeks and Romans made great contributions to the development of adhesives.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Wood veneering and marquetry were developed, the production of animal and fish glues refined, and other materials utilized.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Egg-based pastes were used to bond gold leaves, and incorporated various natural ingredients such as blood, bone, hide, milk, cheese, vegetables, and grains.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The Greeks began the use of slaked lime as mortar while the Romans furthered mortar development by mixing lime with volcanic ash and sand.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] This material, known as pozzolanic cement, was used in the construction of the Roman Colosseum and Pantheon.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The Romans were also the first people known to have used tar and beeswax as caulk and sealant between the wooden planks of their boats and ships.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] In Central Asia, the rise of the Mongols in approximately AD 1000 can be partially attributed to the good range and power of the bows of Genghis Khan's hordes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] These bows were made of a bamboo core, with horn on the belly (facing towards the archer) and sinew on the back, bound together with animal glue.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] In Europe, glue fell into disuse until the period AD 1500–1700.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] At this time, world-renowned cabinet and furniture makers such as Thomas Chippendale and Duncan Phyfe began to use adhesives to hold their products together.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] In 1690, the first commercial glue plant was established in The Netherlands.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] This plant produced glues from animal hides.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] In 1750, the first British glue patent was issued for fish glue.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The following decades of the next century witnessed the manufacture of casein glues in German and Swiss factories.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] In 1876, the first U.S. patent (number 183,024) was issued to the Ross brothers for the production of casein glue.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The first U.S. postage stamps used starch-based adhesives when issued in 1847.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The first US patent (number 61,991) on dextrin (a starch derivative) adhesive was issued in 1867.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Natural rubber was first used as material for adhesives in 1830, which marked the starting point of the modern adhesive.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] In 1862, a British patent (number 3288) was issued for the plating of metal with brass by electrodeposition to obtain a stronger bond to rubber.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The development of the automobile and the need for rubber shock mounts required stronger and more durable bonds of rubber and metal.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] This spurred the development of cyclized rubber treated in strong acids.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] By 1927, this process was used to produce solvent-based thermoplastic rubber cements for metal to rubber bonding.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Natural rubber-based sticky adhesives were first used on a backing by Henry Day (US Patent 3,965) in 1845.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Later these kinds of adhesives were used in cloth backed surgical and electric tapes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] By 1925, the pressure-sensitive tape industry was born.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Today, sticky notes, Scotch Tape, and other tapes are examples of pressure-sensitive adhesives (PSA).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] A key step in the development of synthetic plastics was the introduction of a thermoset plastic known as Bakelite phenolic in 1910.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Within two years, phenolic resin was applied to plywood as a coating varnish.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] In the early 1930s, phenolics gained importance as adhesive resins.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The 1920s, 1930s, and 1940s witnessed great advances in the development and production of new plastics and resins due to the First and Second World Wars.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] These advances greatly improved the development of adhesives by allowing the use of newly developed materials that exhibited a variety of properties.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] With changing needs and ever evolving technology, the development of new synthetic adhesives continues to the present.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] However, due to their low cost, natural adhesives are still more commonly used.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Adhesives are typically organized by the method of adhesion.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] These are then organized into reactive and non-reactive adhesives, which refers to whether the adhesive chemically reacts in order to harden.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Alternatively they can be organized by whether the raw stock is of natural or synthetic origin, or by their starting physical phase.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] There are two types of adhesives that harden by drying: *solvent-based adhesives* and *polymer dispersion adhesives*, also known as *emulsion adhesives*.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Solvent-based adhesives are a mixture of ingredients (typically polymers) dissolved in a solvent.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] White glue, contact adhesives and rubber cements are members of the *drying adhesive* family.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] As the solvent evaporates, the adhesive hardens.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Depending on the chemical composition of the adhesive, they will adhere to different materials to greater or lesser degrees.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Polymer dispersion adhesives are milky-white dispersions often based on polyvinyl acetate (PVAc).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] They are used extensively in the woodworking and packaging industries.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] They are also used with fabrics and fabric-based components, and in engineered products such as loudspeaker cones.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] PSAs are designed for either permanent or removable applications.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Examples of permanent applications include safety labels for power equipment, foil tape for HVAC duct work, automotive interior trim assembly, and sound/vibration damping films.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Some high performance permanent PSAs exhibit high adhesion values and can support kilograms of weight per square centimeter of contact area, even at elevated temperatures.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Permanent PSAs may initially be removable (for example to recover mislabeled goods) and build adhesion to a permanent bond after several hours or days.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Removable adhesives are designed to form a temporary bond, and ideally can be removed after months or years without leaving residue on the adherend.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Some removable adhesives are designed to repeatedly stick and unstick.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] They have low adhesion, and generally cannot support much weight.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Pressure-sensitive adhesive is used in Post-it notes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Pressure-sensitive adhesives are manufactured with either a liquid carrier or in 100% solid form.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Articles are made from liquid PSAs by coating the adhesive and drying off the solvent or water carrier.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] They may be further heated to initiate a cross-linking reaction and increase molecular weight.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] 100% solid PSAs may be low viscosity polymers that are coated and then reacted with radiation to increase molecular weight and form the adhesive, or they may be high viscosity materials that are heated to reduce viscosity enough to allow coating, and then cooled to their final form.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Major raw material for PSA's are acrylate-based polymers.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Contact adhesives must be applied to both surfaces and allowed some time to dry before the two surfaces are pushed together.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Some contact adhesives require as long as 24 hours to dry completely before the surfaces are to be held together.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Once the surfaces are pushed together, the bond forms very quickly.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Clamping is not required due to the rapid bond formation.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Thermoplastic glue may have been invented around 1940 by Procter & Gamble as a solution to the problem that water-based adhesives, commonly used in packaging at that time, failed in humid climates, causing packages to open.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] However, water-based adhesives are still of strong interest as they typically do not contain volatile solvents.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Anaerobic adhesives cure when in contact with metal, in the absence of oxygen.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] They work well in a close-fitting space, as when used as a thread-locking fluid.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] There are several commercial combinations of multi-component adhesives in use in industry.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The individual components of a multi-component adhesive are not adhesive by nature.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The individual components react with each other after being mixed and show full adhesion only on curing.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The multi-component resins can be either solvent-based or solvent-less.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The solvents present in the adhesives are a medium for the polyester or the polyurethane resin.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The solvent is dried during the curing process.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Natural adhesives are made from organic sources such as vegetable starch (dextrin), natural resins, or animals (e.g. the milk protein casein and hide-based animal glues).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] These are often referred to as bioadhesives.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] One example is a simple paste made by cooking flour in water.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Starch-based adhesives are used in corrugated board and paper sack production, paper tube winding, and wallpaper adhesives.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Casein glue is mainly used to adhere glass bottle labels.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Animal glues have traditionally been used in bookbinding, wood joining, and many other areas but now are largely replaced by synthetic glues except in specialist applications like the production and repair of stringed instruments.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Albumen made from the protein component of blood has been used in the plywood industry.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Masonite, a wood hardboard, was originally bonded using natural wood lignin, an organic polymer, though most modern particle boards such as MDF use synthetic thermosetting resins.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Synthetic adhesives are made out of organic compounds.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Many are based on elastomers, thermoplastics, emulsions, and thermosets.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Examples of thermosetting adhesives are: epoxy, polyurethane, cyanoacrylate and acrylic polymers.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The first commercially produced synthetic adhesive was Karlsons Klister in the 1920s.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Applicators of different adhesives are designed according to the adhesive being used and the size of the area to which the adhesive will be applied.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The adhesive is applied to either one or both of the materials being bonded.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The pieces are aligned and pressure is added to aid in adhesion and rid the bond of air bubbles.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Common ways of applying an adhesive include brushes, rollers, using films or pellets, spray guns and applicator guns (*e.g.*, caulk gun).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] All of these can be used manually or automated as part of a machine.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] For an adhesive to be effective it must have three main properties.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Firstly, it must be able to wet the base material.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Wetting is the ability of a liquid to maintain contact with a solid surface.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] It must also increase in strength after application, and finally it must be able to transmit load between the two surfaces/substrates being adhered.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Adhesion, the attachment between adhesive and substrate may occur either by mechanical means, in which the adhesive works its way into small pores of the substrate, or by one of several chemical mechanisms.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The strength of adhesion depends on many factors, including the means by which it occurs.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] In some cases, an actual chemical bond occurs between adhesive and substrate.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Thiolated polymers, for example, form chemical bonds with endogenous proteins such as mucus glycoproteins, integrins or keratins via disulfide bridges.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Because of their comparatively high adhesive properties, these polymers find numerous biomedical applications.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] In others, electrostatic forces, as in static electricity, hold the substances together.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] A third mechanism involves the van der Waals forces that develop between molecules.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] A fourth means involves the moisture-aided diffusion of the glue into the substrate, followed by hardening.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The quality of adhesive bonding depends strongly on the ability of the adhesive to efficiently cover (wet) the substrate area.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] This happens when the surface energy of the substrate is greater than the surface energy of the adhesive.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] However, high-strength adhesives have high surface energy.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Thus, they bond poorly to low-surface-energy polymers or other materials.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] To solve this problem, surface treatment can be used to increase the surface energy as a preparation step before adhesive bonding.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Importantly, surface preparation provides a reproducible surface allowing consistent bonding results.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The commonly used surface activation techniques include plasma activation, flame treatment and wet chemistry priming.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Adhesives can be designed so that they debond when an electric current or electric field is applied, thereby eliminating part damage, or the need for heating.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Depending on the type of adhesive, different health risks present themselves.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Exposure can occur by direct contact or inhalation of fumes and is potentially life-threatening.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] There are several factors that could contribute to the failure of two adhered surfaces.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Sunlight and heat may weaken the adhesive.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Solvents can deteriorate or dissolve adhesive.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Physical stresses may also cause the separation of surfaces.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] When subjected to loading, debonding may occur at different locations in the adhesive joint.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] As a general design rule, the material properties of the object need to be greater than the forces anticipated during its use.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] The engineering work will consist of having a good model to evaluate the function.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] For most adhesive joints, this can be achieved using fracture mechanics.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Concepts such as the stress concentration factor and the strain energy release rate can be used to predict failure.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] In such models, the behavior of the adhesive layer itself is neglected and only the adherents are considered.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Failure will also very much depend on the opening *mode* of the joint.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] As the loads are usually fixed, an acceptable design will result from combination of a material selection procedure and geometry modifications, if possible.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] In adhesively bonded structures, the global geometry and loads are fixed by structural considerations and the design procedure focuses on the material properties of the adhesive and on local changes on the geometry.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Some glues and adhesives have a limited shelf life.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Shelf life is dependent on multiple factors, the foremost of which being temperature.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Adhesives may lose their effectiveness at high temperatures, as well as become increasingly stiff.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/adhesives] Other factors affecting shelf life include exposure to oxygen or water vapor.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] In organic chemistry, an **alkane**, or **paraffin** (a historical trivial name that also has other meanings), is an acyclic saturated hydrocarbon.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] In other words, an alkane consists of hydrogen and carbon atoms arranged in a tree structure in which all the carbon–carbon bonds are single.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Alkanes have the general chemical formula C*n*H2*n*+2.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The alkanes range in complexity from the simplest case of methane (CH4), where *n* = 1 (sometimes called the parent molecule), to arbitrarily large and complex molecules, like hexacontane (C60H122) or 4-methyl-5-(1-methylethyl) octane, an isomer of dodecane (C12H26).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) defines alkanes as "acyclic branched or unbranched hydrocarbons having the general formula C*n*H2*n*+2, and therefore consisting entirely of hydrogen atoms and saturated carbon atoms".
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] However, some sources use the term to denote *any* saturated hydrocarbon, including those that are either monocyclic (i.e. the cycloalkanes) or polycyclic, despite them having a distinct general formula (e.g. cycloalkanes are C*n*H2*n*).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] In an alkane, each carbon atom is sp3-hybridized with 4 sigma bonds (either C–C or C–H), and each hydrogen atom is joined to one of the carbon atoms (in a C–H bond).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The longest series of linked carbon atoms in a molecule is known as its carbon skeleton or carbon backbone.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The number of carbon atoms may be considered as the size of the alkane.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] One group of the higher alkanes are waxes, solids at standard ambient temperature and pressure (SATP), for which the number of carbon atoms in the carbon backbone is greater than about 17.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Methane is produced by methanogenic archaea and some long-chain alkanes function as pheromones in certain animal species or as protective waxes in plants and fungi.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Nevertheless, most alkanes do not have much biological activity.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] They can be viewed as molecular trees upon which can be hung the more active/reactive functional groups of biological molecules.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The alkanes have two main commercial sources: petroleum (crude oil) and natural gas.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] An alkyl group is an alkane-based molecular fragment that bears one open valence for bonding.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] They are generally abbreviated with the symbol for any organyl group, R, although Alk is sometimes used to specifically symbolize an alkyl group (as opposed to an alkenyl group or aryl group).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Ordinarily, the C–C single bond distance is 1.53 ångströms (1.53×10−10 m).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Saturated hydrocarbons can be linear, branched, or cyclic.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The third group is sometimes called cycloalkanes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Very complicated structures are possible by combining linear, branched, cyclic alkanes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Alkanes with more than three carbon atoms can be arranged in various ways, forming structural isomers.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The simplest isomer of an alkane is the one in which the carbon atoms are arranged in a single chain with no branches.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] This isomer is sometimes called the *n*-isomer (*n* for "normal", although it is not necessarily the most common).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] However, the chain of carbon atoms may also be branched at one or more points.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The number of possible isomers increases rapidly with the number of carbon atoms.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] For example, 3-methylhexane and its higher homologues are chiral due to their stereogenic center at carbon atom number 3.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The above list only includes differences of connectivity, not stereochemistry.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] In addition to the alkane isomers, the chain of carbon atoms may form one or more rings.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Such compounds are called cycloalkanes, and are also excluded from the above list because changing the number of rings changes the molecular formula.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] For example, cyclobutane and methylcyclopropane are isomers of each other (C4H8), but are not isomers of butane (C4H10).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Branched alkanes are more thermodynamically stable than their linear (or less branched) isomers.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] For example, the highly branched 2,2,3,3-tetramethylbutane is about 1.9 kcal/mol more stable than its linear isomer, *n*-octane.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The IUPAC nomenclature (systematic way of naming compounds) for alkanes is based on identifying hydrocarbon chains.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Unbranched, saturated hydrocarbon chains are named systematically with a Greek numerical prefix denoting the number of carbons and the suffix "-ane".
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] In 1866, August Wilhelm von Hofmann suggested systematizing nomenclature by using the whole sequence of vowels a, e, i, o and u to create suffixes -ane, -ene, -ine (or -yne), -one, -une, for the hydrocarbons C*n*H2*n*+2, C*n*H2*n*, C*n*H2*n*−2, C*n*H2*n*−4, C*n*H2*n*−6.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] In modern nomenclature, the first three specifically name hydrocarbons with single, double and triple bonds; while "-one" now represents a ketone.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Straight-chain alkanes are sometimes indicated by the prefix *n*- (for "normal") where a non-linear isomer exists.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Alternative names for this group used in the petroleum industry are **linear paraffins** or ***n*-paraffins**.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The first four names were derived from methanol, ether, propionic acid and butyric acid.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Alkanes with five or more carbon atoms are named by adding the suffix **-ane** to the appropriate numerical multiplier prefix with elision of any terminal vowel (*-a* or *-o*) from the basic numerical term.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The numeral prefix is generally Greek; however, alkanes with a carbon atom count ending in nine, for example nonane, use the Latin prefix **non-**.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Simple branched alkanes often have a common name using a prefix to distinguish them from linear alkanes, for example *n*-butane, isobutane (or *i*-butane) for the two isomers of butane and *n*-pentane, isopentane, neopentane for the three isomers of pentane.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] IUPAC naming conventions can be used to produce a systematic name.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Though technically distinct from the alkanes, this class of hydrocarbons is referred to by some as the "cyclic alkanes." As their description implies, they contain one or more rings.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Simple cycloalkanes have a prefix "cyclo-" to distinguish them from alkanes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Cycloalkanes are named as per their acyclic counterparts with respect to the number of carbon atoms in their backbones, e.g., cyclopentane (C5H10) is a cycloalkane with 5 carbon atoms just like pentane (C5H12), but they are joined up in a five-membered ring.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] In a similar manner, propane and cyclopropane, butane and cyclobutane, etc.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Substituted cycloalkanes are named similarly to substituted alkanes – the cycloalkane ring is stated, and the substituents are according to their position on the ring, with the numbering decided by the Cahn–Ingold–Prelog priority rules.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The trivial (non-systematic) name for alkanes is "paraffins".
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Together, alkanes are known as the "paraffin series".
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Trivial names for compounds are usually historical artifacts.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] They were coined before the development of systematic names, and have been retained due to familiar usage in industry.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Cycloalkanes are also called naphthenes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Branched-chain alkanes are called **isoparaffins**.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] "Paraffin" is a general term and often does not distinguish between pure compounds and mixtures of isomers, i.e., compounds of the same chemical formula, e.g., pentane and isopentane.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Alkanes with the lowest molecular weights are gases, those of intermediate molecular weight are liquids, and the heaviest are waxy solids.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Alkanes experiences intermolecular van der Waals forces.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The cumulative effects of these intermolecular forces give rise to greater boiling points of alkanes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Under standard conditions, from CH4 to C4H10 alkanes are gaseous; from C5H12 to C17H36 they are liquids; and after C18H38 they are solids.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] As the boiling point of alkanes is primarily determined by weight, it should not be a surprise that the boiling point has an almost linear relationship with the size (molecular weight) of the molecule.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] As a rule of thumb, the boiling point rises 20–30 °C for each carbon added to the chain; this rule applies to other homologous series.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] A straight-chain alkane will have a boiling point higher than a branched-chain alkane due to the greater surface area in contact, and thus greater van der Waals forces, between adjacent molecules.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] For example, compare isobutane (2-methylpropane) and *n*-butane, which boil at −12 and 0 °C, and 2,2-dimethylbutane and 2,3-dimethylbutane which boil at 50 and 58 °C, respectively.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] On the other hand, cycloalkanes tend to have higher boiling points than their linear counterparts due to the locked conformations of the molecules, which give a plane of intermolecular contact.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The melting points of the alkanes follow a similar trend to boiling points for the same reason as outlined above.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] That is, (all other things being equal) the larger the molecule the higher the melting point.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] However, alkanes' melting points follow a more complex pattern, due to variations in the properties of their solid crystals.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] One difference in crystal structure that even-numbered alkanes (from hexane onwards) tend to form denser-packed crystals compared to their odd-numbered neighbors.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] This causes them to have a greater enthalpy of fusion (amount of energy required to melt them), raising their melting point.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] A second difference in crystal structure is that even-numbered alkanes (from octane onwards) tend to form more rotationally ordered crystals compared to their odd-numbered neighbors.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] This causes them to have a greater entropy of fusion (increase in disorder from the solid to the liquid state), lowering their melting point.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] While these effects operate in opposing directions, the first effect tends to be slightly stronger, leading even-numbered alkanes to have slightly higher melting points than the average of their odd-numbered neighbors.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] This trend does not apply to methane, which has an unusually high melting point, higher than both ethane and propane.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] This is because it has a very low entropy of fusion, attributable to its high molecular symmetry and the rotational disorder in solid methane near its melting point (Methane I).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The melting points of branched-chain alkanes can be either higher or lower than those of the corresponding straight-chain alkanes, again depending on these two factors.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] More symmetric alkanes tend towards higher melting points, due to enthalpic effects when they form ordered crystals, and entropic effects when they form disordered crystals (e.g. neopentane).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Alkanes do not conduct electricity in any way, nor are they substantially polarized by an electric field.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] For this reason, they do not form hydrogen bonds and are insoluble in polar solvents such as water.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Since the hydrogen bonds between individual water molecules are aligned away from an alkane molecule, the coexistence of an alkane and water leads to an increase in molecular order (a reduction in entropy).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] As there is no significant bonding between water molecules and alkane molecules, the second law of thermodynamics suggests that this reduction in entropy should be minimized by minimizing the contact between alkane and water: Alkanes are said to be hydrophobic as they are insoluble in water.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Their solubility in nonpolar solvents is relatively high, a property that is called lipophilicity.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Alkanes are, for example, miscible in all proportions among themselves.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The density of the alkanes usually increases with the number of carbon atoms but remains less than that of water.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Hence, alkanes form the upper layer in an alkane–water mixture.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The molecular structure of the alkanes directly affects their physical and chemical characteristics.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] It is derived from the electron configuration of carbon, which has four valence electrons.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The carbon atoms in alkanes are described as sp3 hybrids; that is to say that, to a good approximation, the valence electrons are in orbitals directed towards the corners of a tetrahedron which are derived from the combination of the 2s orbital and the three 2p orbitals.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] This is exact for the case of methane, while larger alkanes containing a combination of C–H and C–C bonds generally have bonds that are within several degrees of this idealized value.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] An alkane has only C–H and C–C single bonds.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The former result from the overlap of an sp3 orbital of carbon with the 1s orbital of a hydrogen; the latter by the overlap of two sp3 orbitals on adjacent carbon atoms.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The bond lengths amount to 1.09 × 10−10 m for a C–H bond and 1.54 × 10−10 m for a C–C bond.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The spatial arrangement of the bonds is similar to that of the four sp3 orbitals—they are tetrahedrally arranged, with an angle of 109.47° between them.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Structural formulae that represent the bonds as being at right angles to one another, while both common and useful, do not accurately depict the geometry.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The spatial arrangement of the C-C and C-H bonds are described by the torsion angles of the molecule, known as its conformation.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] In ethane, the simplest case for studying the conformation of alkanes, there is nearly free rotation about a carbon–carbon single bond.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Two limiting conformations are important: eclipsed conformation and staggered conformation.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The staggered conformation is 12.6 kJ/mol (3.0 kcal/mol) lower in energy (more stable) than the eclipsed conformation (the least stable).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] In highly branched alkanes, the bond angle may differ from the optimal value (109.5°) to accommodate bulky groups.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Such distortions introduce a tension in the molecule, known as steric hindrance or strain.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Strain substantially increases reactivity.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Spectroscopic signatures for alkanes are obtainable by the major characterization techniques.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The C-H stretching mode gives strong absorptions between 2850 and 2960 cm−1 and weaker bands for the C-C stretching mode absorbs between 800 and 1300 cm−1.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The carbon–hydrogen bending modes depend on the nature of the group: methyl groups show bands at 1450 cm−1 and 1375 cm−1, while methylene groups show bands at 1465 cm−1 and 1450 cm−1.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Carbon chains with more than four carbon atoms show a weak absorption at around 725 cm−1.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The proton resonances of alkanes are usually found at *δ*H = 0.5–1.5.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The carbon-13 resonances depend on the number of hydrogen atoms attached to the carbon: *δ*C = 8–30 (primary, methyl, –CH3), 15–55 (secondary, methylene, –CH2–), 20–60 (tertiary, methyne, C–H) and quaternary.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The carbon-13 resonance of quaternary carbon atoms is characteristically weak, due to the lack of nuclear Overhauser effect and the long relaxation time, and can be missed in weak samples, or samples that have not been run for a sufficiently long time.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Since alkanes have high ionization energies, their electron impact mass spectra show weak currents for their molecular ions.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The fragmentation pattern can be difficult to interpret, but in the case of branched chain alkanes, the carbon chain is preferentially cleaved at tertiary or quaternary carbons due to the relative stability of the resulting free radicals.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The mass spectra for straight-chain alkanes is illustrated by that for dodecane: the fragment resulting from the loss of a single methyl group (*M* − 15) is absent, fragments are more intense than the molecular ion and are spaced by intervals of 14 mass units, corresponding to loss of CH2 groups.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Alkanes are only weakly reactive with most chemical compounds.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] They only react with the strongest of electrophilic reagents by virtue of their strong C–H bonds (~100 kcal/mol) and C–C bonds (~90 kcal/mol).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] They are also relatively unreactive toward free radicals.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] This inertness is the source of the term *paraffins* (with the meaning here of "lacking affinity").
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] In crude oil the alkane molecules have remained chemically unchanged for millions of years.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The acid dissociation constant (p*K*a) values of all alkanes are estimated to range from 50 to 70, depending on the extrapolation method, hence they are extremely weak acids that are practically inert to bases (see: carbon acids).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] They are also extremely weak bases, undergoing no observable protonation in pure sulfuric acid (*H*0 ~ −12), although superacids that are at least millions of times stronger have been known to protonate them to give hypercoordinate alkanium ions (see: methanium ion).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Thus, a mixture of antimony pentafluoride (SbF5) and fluorosulfonic acid (HSO3F), called magic acid, can protonate alkanes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] All alkanes react with oxygen in a combustion reaction, although they become increasingly difficult to ignite as the number of carbon atoms increases.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] See the alkane heat of formation table for detailed data.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The standard enthalpy change of combustion, Δc*H*⊖, for alkanes increases by about 650 kJ/mol per CH2 group.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Branched-chain alkanes have lower values of Δc*H*⊖ than straight-chain alkanes of the same number of carbon atoms, and so can be seen to be somewhat more stable.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Some organisms are capable of metabolizing alkanes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The methane monooxygenases convert methane to methanol.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] For higher alkanes, cytochrome P450 convert alkanes to alcohols, which are then susceptible to degradation.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Free radicals, molecules with unpaired electrons, play a large role in most reactions of alkanes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Free radical halogenation reactions occur with halogens, leading to the production of haloalkanes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The hydrogen atoms of the alkane are progressively replaced by halogen atoms.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The reaction of alkanes and fluorine is highly exothermic and can lead to an explosion.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] These reactions are an important industrial route to halogenated hydrocarbons.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Experiments have shown that all halogenation produces a mixture of all possible isomers, indicating that all hydrogen atoms are susceptible to reaction.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The mixture produced, however, is not statistical: Secondary and tertiary hydrogen atoms are preferentially replaced due to the greater stability of secondary and tertiary free-radicals.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] In the Reed reaction, sulfur dioxide and chlorine convert hydrocarbons to sulfonyl chlorides under the influence of light.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Under some conditions, alkanes will undergo nitration.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Certain transition metal complexes promote non-radical reactions with alkanes, resulting in C–H bond activation reactions.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Cracking breaks larger molecules into smaller ones.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] This reaction requires heat and catalysts.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The thermal cracking process follows a homolytic mechanism with formation of free radicals.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The catalytic cracking process involves the presence of acid catalysts (usually solid acids such as silica-alumina and zeolites), which promote a heterolytic (asymmetric) breakage of bonds yielding pairs of ions of opposite charges, usually a carbocation.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Carbon-localized free radicals and cations are both highly unstable and undergo processes of chain rearrangement, C–C scission in position beta (i.e., cracking) and intra- and intermolecular hydrogen transfer or hydride transfer.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] In both types of processes, the corresponding reactive intermediates (radicals, ions) are permanently regenerated, and thus they proceed by a self-propagating chain mechanism.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The chain of reactions is eventually terminated by radical or ion recombination.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Dragan and his colleague were the first to report about isomerization in alkanes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Isomerization and reformation are processes in which straight-chain alkanes are heated in the presence of a platinum catalyst.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] In isomerization, the alkanes become branched-chain isomers.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] In other words, it does not lose any carbons or hydrogens, keeping the same molecular weight.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] In reformation, the alkanes become cycloalkanes or aromatic hydrocarbons, giving off hydrogen as a by-product.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Both of these processes raise the octane number of the substance.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Butane is the most common alkane that is put under the process of isomerization, as it makes many branched alkanes with high octane numbers.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] In steam reforming, alkanes react with steam in the presence of a nickel catalyst to give hydrogen and carbon monoxide.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Alkanes form a small portion of the atmospheres of the outer gas planets such as Jupiter (0.1% methane, 2 ppm ethane), Saturn (0.2% methane, 5 ppm ethane), Uranus (1.99% methane, 2.5 ppm ethane) and Neptune (1.5% methane, 1.5 ppm ethane).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Titan (1.6% methane), a satellite of Saturn, was examined by the *Huygens* probe, which indicated that Titan's atmosphere periodically rains liquid methane onto the moon's surface.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Also on Titan, the Cassini mission has imaged seasonal methane/ethane lakes near the polar regions of Titan.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Methane and ethane have been detected in the tail of the comet Hyakutake.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Chemical analysis showed that the abundances of ethane and methane were roughly equal, which is thought to imply that its ices formed in interstellar space, away from the Sun, which would have evaporated these volatile molecules.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Alkanes have been detected in meteorites such as carbonaceous chondrites.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Traces of methane gas (about 0.0002% or 1745 ppb) occur in the Earth's atmosphere, produced primarily by methanogenic microorganisms, such as Archaea in the gut of ruminants.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The most important commercial sources for alkanes are natural gas and oil.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Natural gas contains primarily methane and ethane, with some propane and butane: oil is a mixture of liquid alkanes and other hydrocarbons.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] These hydrocarbons were formed when marine animals and plants (zooplankton and phytoplankton) died and sank to the bottom of ancient seas and were covered with sediments in an anoxic environment and converted over many millions of years at high temperatures and high pressure to their current form.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] These hydrocarbon deposits, collected in porous rocks trapped beneath impermeable cap rocks, comprise commercial oil fields.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] They have formed over millions of years and once exhausted cannot be readily replaced.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The depletion of these hydrocarbons reserves is the basis for what is known as the energy crisis.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Alkanes have a low solubility in water, so the content in the oceans is negligible; however, at high pressures and low temperatures (such as at the bottom of the oceans), methane can co-crystallize with water to form a solid methane clathrate (methane hydrate).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Although this cannot be commercially exploited at the present time, the amount of combustible energy of the known methane clathrate fields exceeds the energy content of all the natural gas and oil deposits put together.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Methane extracted from methane clathrate is, therefore, a candidate for future fuels.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Aside from petroleum and natural gas, alkanes occur significantly in nature only as methane, which is produced by some archaea by the process of methanogenesis.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] These organisms are found in the gut of termites and cows.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The methane is produced from carbon dioxide or other organic compounds.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] It is probable that our current deposits of natural gas were formed in a similar way.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Certain types of bacteria can metabolize alkanes: they prefer even-numbered carbon chains as they are easier to degrade than odd-numbered chains.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Alkanes play a negligible role in higher organisms, with rare exception.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Some yeasts, e.g., *Candida tropicale*, *Pichia* sp., *Rhodotorula* sp., can use alkanes as a source of carbon or energy.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The fungus *Amorphotheca resinae* prefers the longer-chain alkanes in aviation fuel, and can cause serious problems for aircraft in tropical regions.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] In plants, the solid long-chain alkanes are found in the plant cuticle and epicuticular wax of many species, but are only rarely major constituents.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] They protect the plant against water loss, prevent the leaching of important minerals by the rain, and protect against bacteria, fungi, and harmful insects.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The carbon chains in plant alkanes are usually odd-numbered, between 27 and 33 carbon atoms in length, and are made by the plants by decarboxylation of even-numbered fatty acids.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The exact composition of the layer of wax is not only species-dependent but also changes with the season and such environmental factors as lighting conditions, temperature or humidity.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The Jeffrey pine is noted for producing exceptionally high levels of *n*-heptane in its resin, for which reason its distillate was designated as the zero point for one octane rating.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Floral scents have also long been known to contain volatile alkane components, and *n*-nonane is a significant component in the scent of some roses.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Emission of gaseous and volatile alkanes such as ethane, pentane, and hexane by plants has also been documented at low levels, though they are not generally considered to be a major component of biogenic air pollution.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Alkanes are important as pheromones, chemical messenger materials, on which insects depend for communication.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] 7-methyltricosane and 9-methyltricosane are active for ladybird beetles (*Adalia bipunctata*).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The emerald ash borer (*Agrilus planipennis Fairmaire*) responds to 9-methylpentacosane.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Female Asian long-horned beetles *Anoplophora glabripennis*, which are very damaging, secrete 2-methyldocosane.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Waggle-dancing honey bees produce and release two alkanes, tricosane and pentacosane.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] One example, in which both plant and animal alkanes play a role, is the ecological relationship between the sand bee (*Andrena nigroaenea*) and the early spider orchid (*Ophrys sphegodes*); the latter is dependent for pollination on the former.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Sand bees use pheromones in order to identify a mate; in the case of *A. nigroaenea*, the females emit a mixture of tricosane (C23H48), pentacosane (C25H52) and heptacosane (C27H56) in the ratio 3:3:1, and males are attracted by specifically this odor.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The orchid takes advantage of this mating arrangement to get the male bee to collect and disseminate its pollen; parts of its flower not only resemble the appearance of sand bees but also produce large quantities of the three alkanes in the same ratio as female sand bees.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] As a result, numerous males are lured to the blooms and attempt to copulate with their imaginary partner: although this endeavor is not crowned with success for the bee, it allows the orchid to transfer its pollen, which will be dispersed after the departure of the frustrated male to other blooms.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The most important source of alkanes is natural gas and crude oil.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Alkanes are separated in an oil refinery by fractional distillation.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Another route to alkanes is hydrogenolysis, which entails cleavage of C-heteroatom bonds using hydrogen.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] In industry, the main substrates are organonitrogen and organosulfur impurities, i.e. the heteroatoms are N and S.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Hydrogenolysis can be applied to the conversion of virtually any functional group into hydrocarbons.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Substrates include haloalkanes, alcohols, aldehydes, ketones, carboxylic acids, etc.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Both hydrogenolysis and hydrogenation are practiced in refineries.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] They can be effected by using lithium aluminium hydride, Clemmenson reduction and other specialized routes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Coal is a more traditional precursor to alkanes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] A wide range of technologies have been intensively practiced for centuries.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Simply heating coal gives alkanes, leaving behind coke.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Relevant technologies include the Bergius process and coal liquefaction.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Partial combustion of coal and related solid organic compounds generates carbon monoxide, which can be hydrogenated using the Fischer–Tropsch process.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] This technology allows the synthesis of liquid hydrocarbons, including alkanes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] This method is used to produce substitutes for petroleum distillates.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Rarely is there any interest in the synthesis of alkanes, since they are usually commercially available and less valued than virtually any precursor.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The best-known method is hydrogenation of alkenes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Many C−X bonds can be converted to C−H bonds using lithium aluminium hydride, Clemmenson reduction, and other specialized routes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Hydrolysis of alkyl Grignard reagents and alkyl organolithium reagents gives alkanes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] The dominant use of alkanes is as fuels.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Propane and butane, easily liquified gases, are commonly known as liquified petroleum gas (LPG).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] From pentane to octane the alkanes are highly volatile liquids.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] They are used as fuels in internal combustion engines, as they vaporize easily on entry into the combustion chamber without forming droplets, which would impair the uniformity of the combustion.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Branched-chain alkanes are preferred as they are much less prone to premature ignition, which causes knocking, than their straight-chain homologues.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] This propensity to premature ignition is measured by the octane rating of the fuel, where 2,2,4-trimethylpentane (*isooctane*) has an arbitrary value of 100, and heptane has a value of zero.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Apart from their use as fuels, the middle alkanes are also good solvents for nonpolar substances.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Alkanes from nonane to, for instance, hexadecane (an alkane with sixteen carbon atoms) are liquids of higher viscosity, less and less suitable for use in gasoline.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] They form instead the major part of diesel and aviation fuel.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Diesel fuels are characterized by their cetane number, cetane being an old name for hexadecane.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] However, the higher melting points of these alkanes can cause problems at low temperatures and in polar regions, where the fuel becomes too thick to flow correctly.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] By the process of cracking, alkanes can be converted to alkenes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Simple alkenes are precursors to polymers, such as polyethylene and polypropylene.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] When the cracking is taken to extremes, alkanes can be converted to carbon black, which is a significant tire component.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Chlorination of methane gives chloromethanes, which are used as solvents and building blocks for complex compounds.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Similarly treatment of methane with sulfur gives carbon disulfide.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Still other chemicals are prepared by reaction with sulfur trioxide and nitric oxide.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Some light hydrocarbons are used as aerosol sprays.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Alkanes from hexadecane upwards form the most important components of fuel oil and lubricating oil.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] In the latter function, they work at the same time as anti-corrosive agents, as their hydrophobic nature means that water cannot reach the metal surface.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Many solid alkanes find use as paraffin wax, for example, in candles.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] This should not be confused however with true wax, which consists primarily of esters.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Alkanes with a chain length of approximately 35 or more carbon atoms are found in bitumen, used, for example, in road surfacing.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] However, the higher alkanes have little value and are usually split into lower alkanes by cracking.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Alkanes are highly flammable, but they have low toxicities.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Methane "is toxicologically virtually inert".
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alkane] Alkanes can be asphyxiants and narcotic.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] An **alum** (/ˈæləm/) is a type of chemical compound, usually a hydrated double sulfate salt of aluminium with the general formula *X*Al(SO4)2·12H2O, such that X is a monovalent cation such as potassium or ammonium.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] By itself, *alum* often refers to potassium alum, with the formula KAl(SO4)2·12H2O.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Other alums are named after the monovalent ion, such as sodium alum and ammonium alum.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] The name *alum* is also used, more generally, for salts with the same formula and structure, except that aluminium is replaced by another trivalent metal ion like chromiumIII, or sulfur is replaced by another chalcogen like selenium.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] The most common of these analogs is chrome alum KCr(SO4)2·12H2O.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] In most industries, the name *alum* (or *papermaker's alum*) is used to refer to aluminium sulfate, Al2(SO4)3·*n*H2O, which is used for most industrial flocculation (the variable n is an integer whose size depends on the amount of water absorbed into the alum).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] For medicine, the word *alum* may also refer to aluminium hydroxide gel used as a vaccine adjuvant.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] The western desert of Egypt was a major source of alum substitutes in antiquity.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] The Ancient Greek Herodotus mentions Egyptian alum as a valuable commodity in his *Histories*.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] The production of potassium alum from alunite is archaeologically attested on the island Lesbos.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] The site was abandoned during the 7th century CE, but dates back at least to the 2nd century CE.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Native *alumen* from the island of Melos appears to have been a mixture mainly of alunogen (Al2(SO4)3·17H2O) with potassium alum and other minor sulfates.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] A detailed description of a substance termed *alumen* occurs in the Roman Pliny the Elder's *Natural History*.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] By comparing Pliny's description with the account of *stypteria* (στυπτηρία) given by Dioscorides, it is obvious the two are identical.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Pliny informs us that a form of *alumen* was found naturally in the earth, and terms it *salsugoterrae*.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Pliny wrote that different substances were distinguished by the name of *alumen*, but they were all characterised by a certain degree of astringency, and were all employed for dyeing and medicine.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Pliny wrote that there is another kind of alum that the ancient Greeks term *schiston*, and which "splits into filaments of a whitish colour".
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] From the name *schiston* and the mode of formation, it seems that this kind was the salt that forms spontaneously on certain salty minerals, as alum slate and bituminous shale, and consists mainly of sulfates of iron and aluminium.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] One kind of *alumen* was a liquid, which was apt to be adulterated; but when pure it had the property of blackening when added to pomegranate juice.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] This property seems to characterize a solution of ironII sulfate in water; a solution of ordinary (potassium) alum would possess no such property.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Contamination with iron sulfate was greatly disliked as this darkened and dulled dye colours.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] In some places the iron sulfate may have been lacking, so the salt would be white and would be suitable, according to Pliny, for dyeing bright colors.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Pliny describes several other types of alumen but it is not clear as to what these minerals are.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] The *alumen* of the ancients, then, was not always potassium alum, not even an alkali aluminum sulfate.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Alum and green vitriol (iron sulfate) both have sweetish and astringent taste, and they had overlapping uses.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Therefore, through the Middle Ages, alchemists and other writers do not seem to have distinguished the two salts accurately.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] In the writings of the alchemists we find the words *misy*, *sory*, and *chalcanthum* applied to either compound; and the name *atramentum sutorium*, which one might expect to belong exclusively to green vitriol, applied indiscriminately to both.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Alum was the most common mordant (substance used to set dyes on fabrics) used by the dye industry, especially in Islamic countries, during the middle ages.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] It was the main export of the Chad region, from where it was transported to the markets of Egypt and Morocco, and then to Europe.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Less significant sources were found in Egypt and Yemen.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Stahl claimed that reacting sulfuric acid with limestone produced a sort of alum.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] The error was soon corrected by Johann Heinrich Pott and Andreas Sigismund Marggraf, who showed that the precipitate obtained when an alkali is poured into a solution of alum, namely alumina, is quite different from lime and chalk, and is one of the ingredients in common clay.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Marggraf also showed that perfect crystals with properties of alum can be obtained by dissolving alumina in sulfuric acid and adding potash or ammonia to the concentrated solution.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] In 1767, Torbern Bergman observed the need for potassium or ammonium sulfates to convert aluminium sulfate into alum, while sodium or calcium would not work.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] The composition of common alum was determined finally by Louis Vauquelin in 1797.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] As soon as Martin Klaproth discovered the presence of potassium in leucite and lepidolite, Vauquelin demonstrated that common alum is a double salt, composed of sulfuric acid, alumina, and potash.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] In the same journal volume, Chaptal published the analysis of four different kinds of alum, namely, Roman alum, Levant alum, British alum, and an alum manufactured by himself, confirming Vauquelin's result.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Some alums occur as minerals, the most important being alunite.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] The most important alums – potassium, sodium, and ammonium – are produced industrially.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Typical recipes involve combining aluminium sulfate and the sulfate monovalent cation.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] The aluminium sulfate is usually obtained by treating minerals like alum schist, bauxite and cryolite with sulfuric acid.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Aluminium-based alums are named by the monovalent cation.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Unlike the other alkali metals, lithium does not form alums, a fact attributed to the small size of its ion.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Aluminium-based alums have a number of common chemical properties.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] They are soluble in water, have a sweetish taste, react as acid by turning blue litmus to red, and crystallize in regular octahedra.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] In alums each metal ion is surrounded by six water molecules.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] When heated, they liquefy, and if the heating is continued, the water of crystallization is driven off, the salt froths and swells, and at last an amorphous powder remains.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Alums crystallize in one of three different crystal structures.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] These classes are called α-, β- and γ-alums.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] The first X-ray crystal structures of alums were reported in 1927 by James M.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Cork and Lawrence Bragg, and were used to develop the phase retrieval technique isomorphous replacement.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] The solubility of the various alums in water varies greatly, sodium alum being soluble readily in water, while caesium and rubidium alums are only slightly soluble.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] The various solubilities are shown in the following table.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Aluminium-based alums have been used since antiquity, and are still important for many industrial processes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] The most widely used alum is potassium alum.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] It has been used since antiquity as a flocculant to clarify cloudy liquids, as a mordant (or binder) in dyeing, and in tanning.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] It is still widely used in water treatment, for medicine, for cosmetics (in deodorant), for food preparation (in baking powder and pickling), and to fire-proof paper and cloth.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Alum is used as a styptic (to stop bleeding) in styptic pencils available from pharmacists.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Alum blocks, available from barber shops and gentlemen's outfitters, are used to stem bleeding from shaving nicks; and as an astringent.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Powdered alum are also used in Southeast Asian traditional medicine for open wounds and sores.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] An alum block can be used directly as a perfume-free deodorant (antiperspirant), and unprocessed mineral alum is sold in Indian bazaars for that purpose.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Throughout Island Southeast Asia, potassium alum is most widely known as *tawas* and has numerous uses.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] It is used as a traditional antiperspirant and deodorant.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] The crystals are usually ground into a fine powder before use.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] In Britain, alum has been used as a way of preserving flour and bleaching it.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Bakers used small amounts to make the fine white manchet bread produced for the rich.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] In times of poor harvest, more alum was added.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] In 1758 the British government banned the use of alum in bread, although some bakers continued to use it and many people continued to demand white bread adulterated with alum.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] During the 19th century, alum was used along with other substances like plaster of Paris to adulterate certain food products, particularly bread.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] It was used to make lower-grade flour appear whiter, allowing the producers to spend less on whiter flour.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Because it retains water, it would make the bread heavier, meaning that merchants could charge more for it in their shops.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] The amount of alum present in each loaf of bread could reach concentrations that would be toxic to humans and cause chronic diarrhoea, which could result in the death of young children.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Alum is used as a mordant in traditional textiles; For traditional Japanese art, alum and animal glue were dissolved in water, forming a liquid known as *dousa* (Japanese: 礬水), and used as an undercoat for paper sizing.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] In Indonesia and the Philippines, solutions of *tawas*, salt, borax, and organic pigments were used to change the color of gold ornaments.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] This is because alum does not react chemically to any significant degree with any of these metals, but will corrode carbon steel.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] When heat is applied to an alum mixture holding a piece of work that has a drill bit stuck in it, if the lost bit is small enough, it can sometimes be dissolved or removed within hours.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] In the Philippines, alum crystals were also burned and allowed to drip into a basin of water by *babaylan* for divination.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] It is also used in other rituals in the animistic anito religions of the islands.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Many trivalent metals are capable of forming alums.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] The general form of an alum is *XY*(SO4)2·*n*H2O, where X is an alkali metal or ammonium, Y is a trivalent metal, and n often is 12.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] The most important example is chrome alum, KCr(SO4)2·12H2O, a dark violet crystalline double sulfate of chromium and potassium, was used in tanning.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] In general, alums are formed more easily when the alkali metal atom is larger.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] This rule was first stated by Locke in 1902, who found that if a trivalent metal does not form a caesium alum, it neither will form an alum with any other alkali metal or with ammonium.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] In some cases, solid solutions of alums with different monovalent and trivalent cations may occur.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] In addition to the alums, which are dodecahydrates, double sulfates and selenates of univalent and trivalent cations occur with other degrees of hydration.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] These classes include differing, but overlapping, combinations of ions.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] A pseudo alum is a double sulfate of the typical formula *X*SO4·*Y*2(SO4)3·22H2O, such that X is a divalent metal ion, such as cobalt (wupatkiite), manganese (apjohnite), magnesium (pickeringite) or iron (halotrichite or feather alum), and Y is a trivalent metal ion.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] The possible combinations of univalent cation, trivalent cation, and anion depends on the sizes of the ions.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] A Tutton salt is a double sulfate of the typical formula *X*2SO4·*Y*SO4·6H2O, where X is a monovalent cation, and Y a divalent metal ion.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/alum] Double sulfates of the composition *X*2SO4·2*Y*SO4, such that X is a monovalent cation and Y is a divalent metal ion are referred to as langbeinites, after the prototypical potassium magnesium sulfate.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-diethyl-phosphinate] In the family of dialkyl phosphinic acid salts, aluminium diethyl phosphinate has been found to be an excellent flame retardant for use in engineering plastics such as polyamides, polyesters, thermosets and elastomers.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-diethyl-phosphinate] It was developed by Hoechst AG, later by Clariant Chemicals and Ticona.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-diethyl-phosphinate] In 2004 and 2012, Clariant chemicals opened its first and second commercial production lines respectively in Huerth-Knapsack near Cologne.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-diethyl-phosphinate] Aluminium diethyl phosphinate acts as a flame retardant in the condensed phase in contributing to charring of the polymer matrix and thus protecting the substrate against heat and oxygen attack.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-diethyl-phosphinate] In parallel it acts in the gas phase by radical reactions removing from the combustion zone the high energy radicals H. and OH., which determine flame propagation and heat release.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-diethyl-phosphinate] The phosphinate partly vaporises and partly decomposes to volatile diethyl phosphinic acid and an aluminium phosphate residue, which acts as a barrier for fuel and heat transport.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-diethyl-phosphinate] Aluminium diethyl phosphinate is used as a halogen-free flame retardant for polyamides, polyesters, thermoset resins (e.g. epoxies) in electrical engineering and electronics (E&E) applications for switches, plugs, PC fans, and structural and housing components.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-diethyl-phosphinate] Mobile phones, washing machines, and airplane parts, among others, contain the product.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-diethyl-phosphinate] Other applications include thermosetting resins and adhesives as well as cable sheaths and insulation made from thermoplastic elastomers.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-diethyl-phosphinate] Aluminium diethyl phosphinate can give these plastics flame retardant properties that are otherwise only achievable with expensive high-performance plastics, which are less easy to work with.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-diethyl-phosphinate] Aluminium diethyl phosphinate is often used in combination with other halogen-free flame retardant additives like melamine polyphosphate or melamine cyanurate.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-diethyl-phosphinate] Here, formulations with aluminium diethyl phosphinate meet the glow wire ignition test (GWIT) at 775 °C and the glow wire flammability test (GWFI) at 960 °C.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-diethyl-phosphinate] Another important criterion in E&E applications is the Comparative Tracking Index (CTI), which determines the risk of electrical tracking of insulating material that is exposed to contaminating environments and surface conditions.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-diethyl-phosphinate] With formulations containing aluminium diethyl phosphinate, the highest requirement of 600 V (numeric value of the highest voltage at which an electrical insulating material withstands 50 drops of electrolytic test solution) is achieved.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-diethyl-phosphinate] Further benefits of polyamides and polyesters containing aluminium diethyl phosphinate are low smoke density which makes them suitable for rolling stock applications to EN 45545, as well as good light stability which is needed for outdoor applications.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-diethyl-phosphinate] The EU’s Restriction of Hazardous Substances Directive forced E&E manufacturers to switch to lead-free solder systems running at about 30 °C higher temperatures than traditional systems.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-diethyl-phosphinate] In particular, in the so-called surface mount technology (SMT) used to connect semiconductor components mechanically and electrically to circuit boards, the resins have to withstand peak temperatures of 260 °C and more during the soldering process.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-diethyl-phosphinate] This triggered the rapid growth of polymer resins based on polyamides with melting points above 300 °C, in particular PPAs and Nylon 46.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-diethyl-phosphinate] The application requires the resin to pass GWIT and UL94 ratings mentioned above.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-diethyl-phosphinate] Aluminium diethylphosphinate confers this flame retardancy on polyamides whilst meeting the other requirements such as CTI.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-diethyl-phosphinate] A large variety of synergists is used to tune properties of polyamide and polyester compounds.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-diethyl-phosphinate] Human health and environmental facts of aluminium diethyl phosphinate are summarized in a fact sheet.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-diethyl-phosphinate] Further data are given in the Arcadis Study carried out on behalf of the European Commission Health & Consumers DG, Contract number 17.020200/09/549040: “Identification and evaluation of data on flame retardants in consumer products.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-diethyl-phosphinate] Aluminium diethyl phosphinate has also been investigated in projects of the US EPA Design for Environment (DfE) programme and in the European FP7 research project Enfiro.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-diethyl-phosphinate] With the exception of being persistent and thus not readily biodegradable, aluminium diethyl phosphinate has been shown to have a favourable environmental and health profile.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] Al(OH)3 is built up of double layers of hydroxyl groups with aluminium ions occupying two-thirds of the octahedral holes between the two layers.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] All feature layers of octahedral aluminium hydroxide units, with hydrogen bonds between the layers.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] The polymorphs differ in terms of the stacking of the layers.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] In acid, it acts as a Brønsted–Lowry base.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] Virtually all the aluminium hydroxide used commercially is manufactured by the Bayer process, which involves dissolving bauxite in sodium hydroxide at temperatures up to 270 °C (518 °F).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] The waste solid, bauxite tailings, is removed and aluminium hydroxide is precipitated from the remaining solution of sodium aluminate.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] This aluminium hydroxide can be converted to aluminium oxide or alumina by calcination.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] The residue (or bauxite tailings), which is mostly composed of iron oxide, is highly caustic due to residual sodium hydroxide.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] It was historically stored in lagoons; this led to the Ajka alumina plant accident in 2010 in Hungary, where a dam bursting led to the drowning of nine people, and an additional 122 sought treatment for chemical burns.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] The mud contaminated 40 square kilometres (15 sq mi) of land and reached the Danube.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] While the mud was considered non-toxic due to low levels of heavy metals, the associated slurry had a pH of 13.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] Aluminium hydroxide finds use as a fire retardant filler for polymer applications.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] It is selected for these applications because it is colorless (like most polymers), inexpensive, and has good fire retardant properties.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] Magnesium hydroxide and mixtures of huntite and hydromagnesite are used similarly.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] These mixtures start to decompose at temperatures around 180 °C (356 °F) to 220 °C (428 °F) (depending on the type of aluminium hydroxide used), absorbing a considerable amount of heat in the process and giving off water vapour.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] The decomposition rate of aluminium hydroxide increases with an increase in temperature, with a reported maximum rate at 250 °C (482 °F).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] In addition to behaving as a fire retardant, it is very effective as a smoke suppressant in a wide range of polymers, most especially in polyesters, acrylics, ethylene vinyl acetate, epoxies, polyvinyl chloride (PVC), rubber, as well as in wood-based products.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] Aluminium hydroxide is used as filler in some artificial stone compound material, often in acrylic resin.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] In the past, freshly precipitated gelatinous aluminium hydroxide was widely used as a mordant for dyeing and calico printing because it can form insoluble coloured lake pigments with vegetable dyes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] Aluminium hydroxide is a feedstock for the manufacture of other aluminium compounds: calcined aluminas, aluminium sulfate, polyaluminium chloride, aluminium chloride, zeolites, sodium aluminate, activated alumina, and aluminium nitrate.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] Freshly precipitated aluminium hydroxide forms gels, which are the basis for the application of aluminium salts as flocculants in water purification.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] Aluminium hydroxide gels can be dehydrated (e.g. using water-miscible non-aqueous solvents like ethanol) to form an amorphous aluminium hydroxide powder, which is readily soluble in acids.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] Heating converts it to activated aluminas, which are used as desiccants, adsorbent in gas purification, and catalyst supports.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] Under the generic name "algeldrate", aluminium hydroxide is used as an antacid in humans and animals (mainly cats and dogs).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] It is preferred over other alternatives such as sodium bicarbonate because Al(OH)3, being insoluble, does not increase the pH of the stomach above 7, and hence does not trigger secretion of excess acid by the stomach.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] Brand names include Alu-Cap, Aludrox, Gaviscon or Pepsamar.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] It reacts with excess acid in the stomach, reducing the acidity of the stomach content, which may relieve the symptoms of ulcers, heartburn or dyspepsia.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] Such products can cause constipation, because the aluminium ions inhibit the contractions of smooth muscle cells in the gastrointestinal tract, slowing peristalsis and lengthening the time needed for stool to pass through the colon.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] Some such products are formulated to minimize such effects through the inclusion of equal concentrations of magnesium hydroxide or magnesium carbonate, which have counterbalancing laxative effects.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] This compound is also used to control hyperphosphatemia (elevated phosphate, or phosphorus, levels in the blood) in people and animals suffering from kidney failure.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] Normally, the kidneys filter excess phosphate out from the blood, but kidney failure can cause phosphate to accumulate.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] The aluminium salt, when ingested, binds to phosphate in the intestines and reduce the amount of phosphorus that can be absorbed.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] Precipitated aluminium hydroxide is included as an adjuvant in some vaccines (e.g. anthrax vaccine).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] One of the well-known brands of aluminium hydroxide adjuvant is Alhydrogel, made by Brenntag Biosector.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] Since it absorbs protein well, it also functions to stabilize vaccines by preventing the proteins in the vaccine from precipitating or sticking to the walls of the container during storage.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] Aluminium hydroxide is sometimes called "alum", a term generally reserved for one of several sulfates.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] Vaccine formulations containing aluminium hydroxide stimulate the immune system by inducing the release of uric acid, an immunological danger signal.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] This strongly attracts certain types of monocytes which differentiate into dendritic cells.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] The dendritic cells pick up the antigen, carry it to lymph nodes, and stimulate T cells and B cells.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] It appears to contribute to induction of a good Th2 response, so is useful for immunizing against pathogens that are blocked by antibodies.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] However, it has little capacity to stimulate cellular (Th1) immune responses, important for protection against many pathogens, nor is it useful when the antigen is peptide-based.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] Aluminium hydroxide is used in chromatography.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] In the 1960s and 1970s it was speculated that aluminium was related to various neurological disorders, including Alzheimer's disease.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] Since then, multiple epidemiological studies have found no connection between exposure to environmental or swallowed aluminium and neurological disorders, though injected aluminium was not looked at in these studies.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] Neural disorders were found in experiments on mice motivated by Gulf War illness (GWI).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminium-hydroxide] Aluminium hydroxide injected in doses equivalent to those administered to the United States military showed increased reactive astrocytes, increased apoptosis of motor neurons, and microglial proliferation within the spinal cord and cortex.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Chemically, aluminium is a post-transition metal in the boron group; as is common for the group, aluminium forms compounds primarily in the +3 oxidation state.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The aluminium cation Al3+ is small and highly charged; as such, it has more polarizing power, and bonds formed by aluminium have a more covalent character.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The strong affinity of aluminium for oxygen leads to the common occurrence of its oxides in nature.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is found on Earth primarily in rocks in the crust, where it is the third-most abundant element after oxygen and silicon, rather than in the mantle, and virtually never as the free metal.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] It is obtained industrially by mining bauxite, a sedimentary rock rich in aluminium minerals.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The discovery of aluminium was announced in 1825 by Danish physicist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The first industrial production of aluminium was initiated by French chemist Henri Étienne Sainte-Claire Deville in 1856.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium became much more available to the public with the Hall–Héroult process developed independently by French engineer Paul Héroult and American engineer Charles Martin Hall in 1886, and the mass production of aluminium led to its extensive use in industry and everyday life.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] In 1954, aluminium became the most produced non-ferrous metal, surpassing copper.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] In the 21st century, most aluminium was consumed in transportation, engineering, construction, and packaging in the United States, Western Europe, and Japan.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The standard atomic weight of aluminium is low in comparison with many other metals, giving it the low density responsible for many of its uses.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Despite its prevalence in the environment, no living thing is known to metabolize aluminium salts, but aluminium is well tolerated by plants and animals.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Because of the abundance of these salts, the potential for a biological role for them is of interest, and studies are ongoing.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium metal has an appearance ranging from silvery white to dull gray depending on its surface roughness.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium mirrors provides high reflectivity for light in the ultraviolet, visible (on par with silver), and far infrared regions.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is also good at reflecting solar radiation, although prolonged exposure to sunlight in air can deteriorate the reflectivity of the metal; this may be prevented if aluminium is anodized, which adds a protective layer of oxide on the surface.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The density of aluminium is 2.70 g/cm3, about one-third that of steel, much lower than other commonly encountered metals, making aluminium parts easily identifiable through their lightness.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium's low density compared to most other metals arises from the fact that its unit cell size is relatively large in proportion to the number of nucleons.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The only lighter metals are the metals of groups 1 and 2, which, apart from beryllium and magnesium, are too reactive for structural use (and beryllium is very toxic).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is not as strong or stiff as steel, but the low density makes up for this in the aerospace industry and for many other applications where light weight and relatively high strength are crucial.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Pure aluminium is quite soft and lacking in strength.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] In most applications, various aluminium alloys are used instead because of their higher strength and hardness.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The yield strength of pure aluminium is 7–11 MPa, while aluminium alloys have yield strengths ranging from 200 MPa to 600 MPa.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is ductile, with a percent elongation of 50–70%, and malleable allowing it to be easily drawn and extruded; it is also easily machined and cast.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is an excellent thermal and electrical conductor, and the amount of aluminium required to match the same amperage in copper weighs only half as much.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is capable of superconductivity, with a superconducting critical temperature of 1.2 kelvin and a critical magnetic field of about 100 gauss (10 milliteslas).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] It is paramagnetic and thus essentially unaffected by static magnetic fields.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] However, the high electrical conductivity means that it is strongly affected by alternating magnetic fields through the induction of eddy currents.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] An aluminium atom has 13 electrons with an electron configuration of [Ne] 3s2 3p1, with three electrons beyond a stable noble gas configuration.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Accordingly, the combined first three ionization energies of aluminium are far lower than the fourth ionization energy alone.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Such an electron configuration is shared with the other well-characterized members of its group, boron, gallium, indium, and thallium; it is also expected for nihonium.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium can surrender its three outermost electrons in many chemical reactions (see below).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The electronegativity of aluminium is 1.61 on the Pauling scale.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] A free aluminium atom has an atomic radius of 143 pm.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] With the three outermost electrons removed, the radius shrinks to 39 pm for a 4-coordinated atom or 53.5 pm for a 6-coordinated atom.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] At standard temperature and pressure, aluminium atoms (when not affected by atoms of other elements) form a face-centered cubic crystal system bound by metallic bonding provided by atoms' outermost electrons; hence, aluminium (at these conditions) is a metal.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] This crystal system is shared by many other metals, such as lead and copper; the size of a unit cell of aluminium is comparable to that of those other metals.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] This system, however, is not shared by the other members of its group: boron has ionization energies too high to allow metallization, thallium has a hexagonal close-packed structure, and gallium and indium have unusual structures that are not close-packed like those of aluminium and thallium.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The few electrons that are available for metallic bonding in aluminium are a probable cause for it being soft with a low melting point and low electrical resistivity.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium has one stable isotope, 27Al, which comprises virtually all of the naturally-occurring element.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] This is common for elements with an odd atomic number.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] It is therefore a mononuclidic element for standard atomic weight, which is determined completely by that isotope.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is useful in nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR), as its single stable isotope (though quadrupolar) has a high NMR sensitivity.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] All other isotopes of aluminium are radioactive.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The most stable of these is 26Al, with a half-life of 717,000 years.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] While it was present along with stable 27Al in the interstellar medium from which the Solar System formed (believed to have been produced by stellar nucleosynthesis also), no detectable amount could have survived the time since the formation of the planet.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] However, minute traces of 26Al are still produced from decay of argon in the atmosphere induced by ionizing radiation of cosmic rays.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The ratio of 26Al to 10Be has been used for the radiodating of geological processes over 105 to 106 year time scales, in particular transport, deposition, sediment storage, burial times, and erosion.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Most meteorite scientists believe that the energy released by the decay of 26Al was responsible for the melting and differentiation of some asteroids after their formation 4.55 billion years ago.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The other known isotopes of aluminium, with mass numbers ranging from 20 to 43, all have half-lives less than 7 minutes, as do the four detected metastable states.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium combines characteristics of pre- and post-transition metals.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Since it has few available electrons for metallic bonding, like the heavier group 13 elements, it has the characteristic physical properties of a post-transition metal, with longer-than-expected interatomic distances.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Furthermore, as Al3+ is a small and highly charged cation, it is strongly polarizing, and bonding in aluminium compounds tends towards covalency; this behavior is similar to that of beryllium (Be2+), displaying an example of a diagonal relationship.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The underlying core of electrons under aluminium's valence shell is that of the preceding noble gas, whereas those of the heavier group 13 elements gallium, indium, thallium, and nihonium also include a filled d-subshell and in some cases a filled f-subshell.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Hence, the inner electrons of aluminium shield the valence electrons almost completely, unlike those of the heavier group 13 elements.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] As such, aluminium is the most electropositive metal in its group, and its hydroxide is in fact more basic than that of gallium.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium also bears minor similarities to boron (a metalloid), which is in the same group: AlX3 compounds are valence isoelectronic to BX3 compounds (they have the same valence electronic structure), and both behave as Lewis acids and readily form adducts.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Additionally, one of the main motifs of boron chemistry is regular icosahedral structures, and aluminium forms an important part of many icosahedral quasicrystal alloys, including the Al–Zn–Mg class.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium has a high chemical affinity to oxygen, which renders it suitable for use as a reducing agent in the thermite reaction.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] A fine powder of aluminium reacts explosively on contact with liquid oxygen; under normal conditions, however, aluminium forms a thin oxide layer (~5 nm at room temperature) that protects the metal from further corrosion by oxygen, water, or dilute acid, a process termed passivation.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is not attacked by oxidizing acids because of its passivation.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] This allows aluminium to be used to store reagents such as nitric acid, concentrated sulfuric acid, and some organic acids.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] In hot, concentrated hydrochloric acid, aluminium reacts with water through evolution of hydrogen, and it reacts in aqueous sodium or potassium hydroxide at room temperature to form aluminates; protective passivation under these conditions is negligible.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is also corroded by dissolved chlorides, such as common sodium chloride.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The oxide layer on aluminium is also destroyed by contact with mercury due to amalgamation or by contact with salts of some electropositive metals.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] As such, the strongest aluminium alloys are less corrosion-resistant due to galvanic reactions with alloyed copper, and aluminium's corrosion resistance is greatly reduced by aqueous salts, particularly in the presence of dissimilar metals.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium reacts with most nonmetals upon heating, forming compounds such as aluminium nitride (AlN), aluminium sulfide (Al2S3), and the aluminium halides (AlX3).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] It also forms a wide range of intermetallic compounds involving metals from every group on the periodic table.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The vast majority of aluminium compounds, including all aluminium-containing minerals and all commercially significant aluminium compounds, feature aluminium in the oxidation state 3+.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The coordination number of such compounds varies, but generally Al3+ is either six- or four-coordinate.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Almost all compounds of aluminium(III) are colorless.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] In aqueous solution, Al3+ exists as the hexa-aqua cation [Al(H2O)6]3+, which has an approximate Ka of 10−5.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Such solutions are acidic because this cation can act as a proton donor and progressively hydrolyze until a precipitate of aluminium hydroxide, Al(OH)3, forms.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] This is useful for clarification of water, since the precipitate nucleates on suspended particles in the water, hence removing them.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Increasing the pH even further leads to the hydroxide dissolving again as aluminate, [Al(H2O)2(OH)4]−, is formed.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium hydroxide forms both salts and aluminates and dissolves in acid and alkali, as well as on fusion with acidic and basic oxides.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] This behavior of Al(OH)3 is termed amphoterism and is characteristic of weakly basic cations that form insoluble hydroxides and whose hydrated species can also donate their protons.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] One effect of this is that aluminium salts with weak acids are hydrolyzed in water to the aquated hydroxide and the corresponding nonmetal hydride: for example, aluminium sulfide yields hydrogen sulfide.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] However, some salts like aluminium carbonate exist in aqueous solution but are unstable as such.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Only incomplete hydrolysis takes place for salts with strong acids, such as the halides, nitrate, and sulfate.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] For similar reasons, anhydrous aluminium salts cannot be made by heating their "hydrates": hydrated aluminium chloride is in fact not AlCl3·6H2O but [Al(H2O)6]Cl3, and the Al–O bonds are so strong that heating is not sufficient to break them and form Al–Cl bonds.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Unlike the structures of the three heavier trihalides, aluminium fluoride (AlF3) features six-coordinate aluminium, which explains its involatility and insolubility as well as high heat of formation.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Each aluminium atom is surrounded by six fluorine atoms in a distorted octahedral arrangement, with each fluorine atom being shared between the corners of two octahedra.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Such {AlF6} units also exist in complex fluorides such as cryolite, Na3AlF6.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] AlF3 melts at 1,290 °C (2,354 °F) and is made by reaction of aluminium oxide with hydrogen fluoride gas at 700 °C (1,300 °F).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] With heavier halides, the coordination numbers are lower.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The other trihalides are dimeric or polymeric with tetrahedral four-coordinate aluminium centers.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium trichloride (AlCl3) has a layered polymeric structure below its melting point of 192.4 °C (378 °F) but transforms on melting to Al2Cl6 dimers.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] At higher temperatures those increasingly dissociate into trigonal planar AlCl3 monomers similar to the structure of BCl3.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium tribromide and aluminium triiodide form Al2X6 dimers in all three phases and hence do not show such significant changes of properties upon phase change.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] These materials are prepared by treating aluminium with the halogen.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The aluminium trihalides form many addition compounds or complexes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Their Lewis acidic nature makes them useful as catalysts for the Friedel–Crafts reactions.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium trichloride has major industrial uses involving this reaction, such as in the manufacture of anthraquinones and styrene.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium trichloride is also often used as the precursor for many other aluminium compounds and as a reagent for converting nonmetal fluorides into the corresponding chlorides (a transhalogenation reaction).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium forms one stable oxide with the chemical formula Al2O3, commonly called alumina.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] It can be found in nature in the mineral corundum, the α-alumina phase.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Its crystalline form, corundum, is very hard (Mohs hardness 9), has a high melting point of 2,045 °C (3,713 °F), has very low volatility, is chemically inert, and is a good electrical insulator.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] It is often used in abrasives (such as sandpaper) as a refractory material and in ceramics.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] It is also the starting material for the electrolytic production of aluminium.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Sapphire and ruby are impure corundum contaminated with trace amounts of other metals.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The two main oxide-hydroxides, AlO(OH), are boehmite and diaspore.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] There are three main trihydroxides: bayerite, gibbsite, and nordstrandite, which differ in their crystalline structure (polymorphs).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Many other intermediate and related structures are also known.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Most of these Al-O-OH systems are produced from ores by a variety of wet processes using acid and bases.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Heating the hydroxides leads to the formation of corundum.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] These materials are of central importance to the production of aluminium and are themselves extremely useful.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Some mixed oxide phases are also very useful, such as spinel (MgAl2O4), Na-β-alumina (NaAl11O17), and tricalcium aluminate (Ca3Al2O6), an important mineral phase in Portland cement.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The only stable chalcogenides under normal conditions are aluminium sulfide (Al2S3), selenide (Al2Se3), and telluride (Al2Te3).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] All three are prepared by direct reaction of their elements at about 1,000 °C (1,800 °F) and quickly hydrolyze completely in water to yield aluminium hydroxide and the respective hydrogen chalcogenide.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] As aluminium is a small atom relative to these chalcogens, these have four-coordinate tetrahedral aluminium with various polymorphs having structures related to wurtzite, with two-thirds of the possible metal sites occupied either in an orderly (α) or random (β) fashion.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The sulfide also has a γ form related to γ-alumina and an unusual high-temperature hexagonal form where half the aluminium atoms have tetrahedral four-coordination and the other half have trigonal bipyramidal five-coordination.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Four pnictides – aluminium nitride (AlN), aluminium phosphide (AlP), aluminium arsenide (AlAs), and aluminium antimonide (AlSb) – are known.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] They are all III-V semiconductors isoelectronic to silicon and germanium, all of which but AlN have the zinc blende structure.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] All four can be made by high-temperature (and possibly high-pressure) direct reaction of their component elements.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium alloys well with most other metals (with the exception of most alkali metals and group 13 metals) and over 150 intermetallics with other metals are known.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Preparation involves heating fixed metals together in certain proportions, followed by gradual cooling and annealing.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Bonding in them is predominantly metallic and the crystal structure primarily depends on efficiency of packing.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] There are few compounds with lower oxidation states.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Some are aluminium(I) compounds: AlF, AlCl, AlBr, and AlI all exist in the gaseous phase when the respective trihalide is heated with aluminium, and at cryogenic temperatures.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] A stable derivative of aluminium monoiodide is the cyclic adduct formed with triethylamine, Al4I4(NEt3)4.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Al2O and Al2S also exist but are very unstable.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Very simple aluminium(II) compounds are invoked or observed in the reactions of Al metal with oxidants.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] For example, aluminium monoxide, AlO, has been detected in the gas phase after explosion and in stellar absorption spectra.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] More thoroughly investigated are compounds of the formula R4Al2 which contain an Al–Al bond and where R is a large organic ligand.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] A variety of compounds of empirical formula AlR3 and AlR1.5Cl1.5 exist.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The aluminium trialkyls and triaryls are either reactive, volatile, and colorless liquids or low-melting solids.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] They catch fire spontaneously in air and react with water, thus necessitating precautions when handling them.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] They often form dimers, unlike their boron analogues, but this tendency diminishes for branched-chain alkyls (e.g.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] For example, triisobutylaluminium exists as an equilibrium mixture of the monomer and dimer.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] These dimers, such as trimethylaluminium (Al2Me6), usually feature tetrahedral Al centers formed by dimerization with some alkyl group bridging between both aluminium atoms.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] They are hard acids and react readily with ligands, forming adducts.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] In industry, they are mostly used in alkene insertion reactions, as discovered by Karl Ziegler, most importantly in "growth reactions" that form long-chain unbranched primary alkenes and alcohols, and in the low-pressure polymerization of ethene and propene.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] There are also some heterocyclic and cluster organoaluminium compounds involving Al–N bonds.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The industrially most important aluminium hydride is lithium aluminium hydride (LiAlH4), which is used as a reducing agent in organic chemistry.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] It can be produced from lithium hydride and aluminium trichloride.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The simplest hydride, aluminium hydride or alane, is not as important.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] It is a polymer with the formula (AlH3)*n*, which is in contrast to the corresponding boron hydride that is a dimer with the formula (BH3)2.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium's per-particle abundance in the Solar System is 3.15 ppm (parts per million).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] It is the twelfth most abundant of all elements and third most abundant among the elements that have odd atomic numbers, after hydrogen and nitrogen.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The only stable isotope of aluminium, 27Al, is the eighteenth most abundant nucleus in the universe.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] It is created almost entirely after fusion of carbon in massive stars that will later become Type II supernovas: this fusion creates 26Mg, which upon capturing free protons and neutrons, becomes aluminium.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Some smaller quantities of 27Al are created in hydrogen burning shells of evolved stars, where 26Mg can capture free protons.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Essentially all aluminium now in existence is 27Al.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] 26Al was present in the early Solar System with abundance of 0.005% relative to 27Al but its half-life of 728,000 years is too short for any original nuclei to survive; 26Al is therefore extinct.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Unlike for 27Al, hydrogen burning is the primary source of 26Al, with the nuclide emerging after a nucleus of 25Mg catches a free proton.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] However, the trace quantities of 26Al that do exist are the most common gamma ray emitter in the interstellar gas; if the original 26Al were still present, gamma ray maps of the Milky Way would be brighter.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Overall, the Earth is about 1.59% aluminium by mass (seventh in abundance by mass).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium occurs in greater proportion in the Earth's crust than in the universe at large.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] This is because aluminium easily forms the oxide and becomes bound into rocks and stays in the Earth's crust, while less reactive metals sink to the core.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] In the Earth's crust, aluminium is the most abundant metallic element (8.23% by mass) and the third most abundant of all elements (after oxygen and silicon).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] A large number of silicates in the Earth's crust contain aluminium.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] In contrast, the Earth's mantle is only 2.38% aluminium by mass.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium also occurs in seawater at a concentration of 0.41 μg/kg.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Because of its strong affinity for oxygen, aluminium is almost never found in the elemental state; instead it is found in oxides or silicates.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Feldspars, the most common group of minerals in the Earth's crust, are aluminosilicates.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium also occurs in the minerals beryl, cryolite, garnet, spinel, and turquoise.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Impurities in alumina yield gemstones: for example, chromium yields ruby and iron yields sapphire.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Native aluminium metal is extremely rare and can only be found as a minor phase in low oxygen fugacity environments, such as the interiors of certain volcanoes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Native aluminium has been reported in cold seeps in the northeastern continental slope of the South China Sea.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] It is possible that these deposits resulted from bacterial reduction of tetrahydroxoaluminate Al(OH)4−.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Although aluminium is a common and widespread element, not all aluminium minerals are economically viable sources of the metal.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Almost all metallic aluminium is produced from the ore bauxite (AlO*x*(OH)3–2*x*).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Bauxite occurs as a weathering product of low iron and silica bedrock in tropical climatic conditions.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] In 2017, most bauxite was mined in Australia, China, Guinea, and India.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The history of aluminium has been shaped by usage of alum.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The first written record of alum, made by Greek historian Herodotus, dates back to the 5th century BCE.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The ancients are known to have used alum as a dyeing mordant and for city defense as a fire-resistant coating for wood.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] After the Crusades, alum, an indispensable good in the European fabric industry, was a subject of international commerce; it was imported to Europe from the eastern Mediterranean until the mid-15th century.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The nature of alum remained unknown until Swiss physician Paracelsus suggested alum was a salt of an earth of alum around 1530.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] German doctor and chemist Andreas Libavius experimentally confirmed this in 1595.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] German chemist Friedrich Hoffmann announced his belief that the base of alum was a distinct earth in 1722.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] German chemist Andreas Sigismund Marggraf synthesized alumina in 1754 by boiling clay in sulfuric acid and subsequently adding potash.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Attempts to produce aluminium date back to 1760.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The first successful attempt, however, was completed in 1824 by Danish physicist and chemist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] He reacted anhydrous aluminium chloride with potassium amalgam, yielding a lump of metal looking similar to tin.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] He presented his results and demonstrated a sample of the new metal in 1825.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] In 1827, German chemist Friedrich Wöhler repeated Ørsted's experiments but did not identify any aluminium.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] (The reason for this inconsistency was only discovered in 1921.) He conducted a similar experiment in the same year by mixing anhydrous aluminium chloride with potassium (the Wöhler process) and produced a powder of aluminium.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] In 1845, he was able to produce small pieces of the metal and described some physical properties of this metal.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] For many years thereafter, Wöhler was credited as the discoverer of aluminium.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] As Wöhler's method could not yield great quantities of aluminium, the metal remained rare; its cost exceeded that of gold.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The first industrial production of aluminium was established in 1856 by French chemist Henri Étienne Sainte-Claire Deville and companions.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Sainte-Claire Deville had discovered that aluminium trichloride could be reduced by sodium, which was more convenient and less expensive than potassium, which Wöhler had used.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Even then, aluminium was still not of great purity and produced aluminium differed in properties by sample.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Because of its electricity-conducting capacity, aluminium was used as the cap of the Washington Monument, completed in 1885, the tallest building in the world at the time.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The non-corroding metal cap was intended to serve as a lightning rod peak.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The first industrial large-scale production method was independently developed in 1886 by French engineer Paul Héroult and American engineer Charles Martin Hall; it is now known as the Hall–Héroult process.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The Hall–Héroult process converts alumina into metal.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Austrian chemist Carl Joseph Bayer discovered a way of purifying bauxite to yield alumina, now known as the Bayer process, in 1889.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Modern production of aluminium is based on the Bayer and Hall–Héroult processes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] As large-scale production caused aluminium prices to drop, the metal became widely used in jewelry, eyeglass frames, optical instruments, tableware, and foil, and other everyday items in the 1890s and early 20th century.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium's ability to form hard yet light alloys with other metals provided the metal with many uses at the time.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] During World War I, major governments demanded large shipments of aluminium for light strong airframes; during World War II, demand by major governments for aviation was even higher.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] From the early 20th century to 1980, the aluminium industry was characterized by cartelization, as aluminium firms colluded to keep prices high and stable.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The first aluminium cartel, the Aluminium Association, was founded in 1901 by the Pittsburgh Reduction Company (renamed Alcoa in 1907) and Aluminium Industrie AG.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The British Aluminium Company, Produits Chimiques d'Alais et de la Camargue, and Société Électro-Métallurgique de Froges also joined the cartel.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] By the mid-20th century, aluminium had become a part of everyday life and an essential component of housewares.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] In 1954, production of aluminium surpassed that of copper, historically second in production only to iron, making it the most produced non-ferrous metal.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] During the mid-20th century, aluminium emerged as a civil engineering material, with building applications in both basic construction and interior finish work, and increasingly being used in military engineering, for both airplanes and armored vehicle engines.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Earth's first artificial satellite, launched in 1957, consisted of two separate aluminium semi-spheres joined and all subsequent space vehicles have used aluminium to some extent.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The aluminium can was invented in 1956 and employed as a storage for drinks in 1958.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Throughout the 20th century, the production of aluminium rose rapidly: while the world production of aluminium in 1900 was 6,800 metric tons, the annual production first exceeded 100,000 metric tons in 1916; 1,000,000 tons in 1941; 10,000,000 tons in 1971.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] In the 1970s, the increased demand for aluminium made it an exchange commodity; it entered the London Metal Exchange, the oldest industrial metal exchange in the world, in 1978.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The output continued to grow: the annual production of aluminium exceeded 50,000,000 metric tons in 2013.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The real price for aluminium declined from $14,000 per metric ton in 1900 to $2,340 in 1948 (in 1998 United States dollars).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Extraction and processing costs were lowered over technological progress and the scale of the economies.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] However, the need to exploit lower-grade poorer quality deposits and the use of fast increasing input costs (above all, energy) increased the net cost of aluminium; the real price began to grow in the 1970s with the rise of energy cost.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Production moved from the industrialized countries to countries where production was cheaper.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Production costs in the late 20th century changed because of advances in technology, lower energy prices, exchange rates of the United States dollar, and alumina prices.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The BRIC countries' combined share in primary production and primary consumption grew substantially in the first decade of the 21st century.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] China is accumulating an especially large share of the world's production thanks to an abundance of resources, cheap energy, and governmental stimuli; it also increased its consumption share from 2% in 1972 to 40% in 2010.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] In the United States, Western Europe, and Japan, most aluminium was consumed in transportation, engineering, construction, and packaging.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] In 2021, prices for industrial metals such as aluminium have soared to near-record levels as energy shortages in China drive up costs for electricity.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The names *aluminium* and *aluminum* are derived from the word *alumine*, an obsolete term for *alumina*, the primary naturally occurring oxide of aluminium.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] *Alumine* was borrowed from French, which in turn derived it from *alumen*, the classical Latin name for alum, the mineral from which it was collected.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The Latin word *alumen* stems from the Proto-Indo-European root **alu-* meaning "bitter" or "beer".
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The English name *alum* does not come directly from Latin, whereas *alumine*/*alumina* comes from the Latin word *alumen* (on declension, *alumen* changes to *alumin-*).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] British chemist Humphry Davy, who performed a number of experiments aimed to isolate the metal, is credited as the person who named the element.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The first name proposed for the metal to be isolated from alum was *alumium*, which Davy suggested in an 1808 article on his electrochemical research, published in Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] It appeared that the name was created from the English word *alum* and the Latin suffix *-ium*; but it was customary then to give elements names originating in Latin, so this name was not adopted universally.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The name *alumium* was criticized by contemporary chemists from France, Germany, and Sweden, who insisted the metal should be named for the oxide, alumina, from which it would be isolated.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] One example was *Essai sur la Nomenclature chimique* (July 1811), written in French by a Swedish chemist, Jöns Jacob Berzelius, in which the name *aluminium* is given to the element that would be synthesized from alum.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] (Another article in the same journal issue also refers to the metal whose oxide is the basis of sapphire, i.e., the same metal, as to *aluminium*.) A January 1811 summary of one of Davy's lectures at the Royal Society mentioned the name *aluminium* as a possibility.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] In 1812, Davy published his chemistry text *Elements of Chemical Philosophy* in which he used the spelling *aluminum*.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] In 1812, British scientist Thomas Young wrote an anonymous review of Davy's book, in which he proposed the name *aluminium* instead of *aluminum*, which he thought had a "less classical sound".
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] This name persisted: although the *-um* spelling was occasionally used in Britain, the American scientific language used *-ium* from the start.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The French have used the spelling *aluminium* from the start.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Most scientists throughout the world used *-ium* in the 19th century; and it was entrenched in several other European languages, such as French, German, and Dutch.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] In 1828, an American lexicographer, Noah Webster, entered only the *aluminum* spelling in his *American Dictionary of the English Language*.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] In the 1830s, the *-um* spelling gained usage in the United States; by the 1860s, it had become the more common spelling there outside science.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] In 1892, Hall used the *-um* spelling in his advertising handbill for his new electrolytic method of producing the metal, despite his constant use of the *-ium* spelling in all the patents he filed between 1886 and 1903.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] It is unknown whether this spelling was introduced by mistake or intentionally, but Hall preferred *aluminum* since its introduction because it resembled *platinum*, the name of a prestigious metal.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] By 1890, both spellings had been common in the United States, the *-ium* spelling being slightly more common; by 1895, the situation had reversed; by 1900, *aluminum* had become twice as common as *aluminium*; in the next decade, the *-um* spelling dominated American usage.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] In 1925, the American Chemical Society adopted the spelling *aluminum*.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) adopted *aluminium* as the standard international name for the element in 1990.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] In 1993, they recognized *aluminum* as an acceptable variant; the most recent 2005 edition of the IUPAC nomenclature of inorganic chemistry also acknowledges this spelling.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] IUPAC official publications use the *-ium* spelling as primary, and they list both where it is appropriate.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Their usage is currently regional: *aluminum* dominates in the United States and Canada; *aluminium* is prevalent in the rest of the English-speaking world.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] German physicist Ludwig Wilhelm Gilbert had proposed *Thonerde-metall*, after the German *Thonerde* for alumina, in his *Annalen der Physik* but that name never caught on at all even in Germany.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Richards in 1891 found just one occurrence of *argillium* in Swedish, from the French *argille* for clay.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The production of aluminium starts with the extraction of bauxite rock from the ground.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The bauxite is processed and transformed using the Bayer process into alumina, which is then processed using the Hall–Héroult process, resulting in the final aluminium.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium production is highly energy-consuming, and so the producers tend to locate smelters in places where electric power is both plentiful and inexpensive.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Production of one kilogram of aluminium requires 7 kilograms of oil energy equivalent, as compared to 1.5 kilograms for steel and 2 kilograms for plastic.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] As of 2024, the world's largest producers of aluminium were China, India, Russia, Canada, and the United Arab Emirates, while China is by far the top producer of aluminium with a world share of over 55%.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] According to the International Resource Panel's Metal Stocks in Society report, the global per capita stock of aluminium in use in society (i.e. in cars, buildings, electronics, etc.) is 80 kg (180 lb).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Much of this is in more-developed countries (350–500 kg (770–1,100 lb) per capita) rather than less-developed countries (35 kg (77 lb) per capita).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Bauxite is converted to alumina by the Bayer process.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Bauxite is blended for uniform composition and then is ground fine.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] After this reaction, the slurry is at a temperature above its atmospheric boiling point.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] It is cooled by removing steam as pressure is reduced.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The bauxite residue is separated from the solution and discarded.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The solution, free of solids, is seeded with small crystals of aluminium hydroxide; this causes decomposition of the [Al(OH)4]− ions to aluminium hydroxide.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] After about half of aluminium has precipitated, the mixture is sent to classifiers.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Small crystals of aluminium hydroxide are collected to serve as seeding agents; coarse particles are converted to alumina by heating; the excess solution is removed by evaporation, (if needed) purified, and recycled.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The conversion of alumina to aluminium is achieved by the Hall–Héroult process.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] In this energy-intensive process, a solution of alumina in a molten (940 and 970 °C (1,720 and 1,780 °F)) mixture of cryolite (Na3AlF6) with calcium fluoride is electrolyzed to produce metallic aluminium.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The liquid aluminium sinks to the bottom of the solution and is tapped off, and usually cast into large blocks called aluminium billets for further processing.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Anodes of the electrolysis cell are made of carbon—the most resistant material against fluoride corrosion—and either bake at the process or are prebaked.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The former, also called Söderberg anodes, are less power-efficient and fumes released during baking are costly to collect, which is why they are being replaced by prebaked anodes even though they save the power, energy, and labor to prebake the cathodes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Carbon for anodes should be preferably pure so that neither aluminium nor the electrolyte is contaminated with ash.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Despite carbon's resistivity against corrosion, it is still consumed at a rate of 0.4–0.5 kg per each kilogram of produced aluminium.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Cathodes are made of anthracite; high purity for them is not required because impurities leach only very slowly.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The cathode is consumed at a rate of 0.02–0.04 kg per each kilogram of produced aluminium.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] A cell is usually terminated after 2–6 years following a failure of the cathode.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The Hall–Heroult process produces aluminium with a purity of above 99%.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Further purification can be done by the Hoopes process.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] This process involves the electrolysis of molten aluminium with a sodium, barium, and aluminium fluoride electrolyte.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The resulting aluminium has a purity of 99.99%.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Electric power represents about 20 to 40% of the cost of producing aluminium, depending on the location of the smelter.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium production consumes roughly 5% of electricity generated in the United States.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Because of this, alternatives to the Hall–Héroult process have been researched, but none has turned out to be economically feasible.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Recovery of the metal through recycling has become an important task of the aluminium industry.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Recycling was a low-profile activity until the late 1960s, when the growing use of aluminium beverage cans brought it to public awareness.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Recycling involves melting the scrap, a process that requires only 5% of the energy used to produce aluminium from ore, though a significant part (up to 15% of the input material) is lost as dross (ash-like oxide).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] An aluminium stack melter produces significantly less dross, with values reported below 1%.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] White dross from primary aluminium production and from secondary recycling operations still contains useful quantities of aluminium that can be extracted industrially.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The process produces aluminium billets, together with a highly complex waste material.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] It reacts with water, releasing a mixture of gases including, among others, acetylene, hydrogen sulfide and significant amounts of ammonia.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Despite these difficulties, the waste is used as a filler in asphalt and concrete.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Its potential for hydrogen production has also been considered and researched.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The global production of aluminium in 2016 was 58.8 million metric tons.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] It exceeded that of any other metal except iron (1,231 million metric tons).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is almost always alloyed, which markedly improves its mechanical properties, especially when tempered.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] For example, the common aluminium foils and beverage cans are alloys of 92% to 99% aluminium.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The main alloying agents for both wrought and cast aluminium are copper, zinc, magnesium, manganese, and silicon (e.g., duralumin) with the levels of other metals in a few percent by weight.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is the main substitute to copper and its applications to the traditional domains of copper have seen increased interest when copper prices are high such as in 2011–2014 and 2021.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] There is a competition in the use of aluminium and copper in the automotive industry, but in other uses such as in the construction industry and in underground and submarine cables aluminium has been largely unable to compete with copper.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The great majority (about 90%) of aluminium oxide is converted to metallic aluminium.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Being a very hard material (Mohs hardness 9), alumina is widely used as an abrasive; being extraordinarily chemically inert, it is useful in highly reactive environments such as high pressure sodium lamps.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium oxide is commonly used as a catalyst for industrial processes; e.g. the Claus process to convert hydrogen sulfide to sulfur in refineries and to alkylate amines.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Many industrial catalysts are supported by alumina, meaning that the expensive catalyst material is dispersed over a surface of the inert alumina.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Another principal use is as a drying agent or absorbent.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Several sulfates of aluminium have industrial and commercial application.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium sulfate (in its hydrate form) is produced on the annual scale of several millions of metric tons.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] About two-thirds is consumed in water treatment.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] The next major application is in the manufacture of paper.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] It is also used as a mordant in dyeing, in pickling seeds, deodorizing of mineral oils, in leather tanning, and in production of other aluminium compounds.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Two kinds of alum, ammonium alum and potassium alum, were formerly used as mordants and in leather tanning, but their use has significantly declined following availability of high-purity aluminium sulfate.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Anhydrous aluminium chloride is used as a catalyst in chemical and petrochemical industries, the dyeing industry, and in synthesis of various inorganic and organic compounds.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Aluminium hydroxychlorides are used in purifying water, in the paper industry, and as antiperspirants.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p01] Sodium aluminate is used in treating water and as an accelerator of solidification of cement.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] Despite its widespread occurrence in the Earth's crust, aluminium has no known function in biology.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] At pH 6–9 (relevant for most natural waters), aluminium precipitates out of water as the hydroxide and is hence not available; most elements behaving this way have no biological role or are toxic.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] Aluminium sulfate has an LD50 of 6207 mg/kg (oral, mouse).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] Aluminium is classified as a non-carcinogen by the United States Department of Health and Human Services.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] A review published in 1988 said that there was little evidence that normal exposure to aluminium presents a risk to healthy adult, and a 2014 multi-element toxicology review was unable to find deleterious effects of aluminium consumed in amounts not greater than 40 mg/day per kg of body mass.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] Most ingested aluminium is eliminated in feces, and much of what enters the bloodstream is excreted in urine; however, not all absorbed or parenterally administered aluminium is cleared through urinary excretion.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] Aluminium, although rarely, can cause vitamin D-resistant osteomalacia, erythropoietin-resistant microcytic anemia, and central nervous system alterations.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] People with kidney insufficiency are especially at a risk.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] Chronic ingestion of hydrated aluminium silicates (for excess gastric acidity control) may result in aluminium binding to intestinal contents and increased elimination of other metals, such as iron or zinc; sufficiently high doses (>50 g/day) can cause anemia.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] During the 1988 Camelford water pollution incident, people in Camelford had their drinking water contaminated with aluminium sulfate for several weeks.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] A final report into the incident in 2013 concluded it was unlikely that this had caused long-term health problems.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] Aluminium has been suspected of being a possible cause of Alzheimer's disease, but research into this for over 40 years has found, as of 2018, no good evidence of causal effect.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] Aluminium increases estrogen-related gene expression in human breast cancer cells cultured in the laboratory.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] In very high doses, aluminium is associated with altered function of the blood–brain barrier.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] A small percentage of people have contact allergies to aluminium and experience itchy red rashes, headache, muscle pain, joint pain, poor memory, insomnia, depression, asthma, irritable bowel syndrome, or other symptoms upon contact with products containing aluminium.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] Exposure to powdered aluminium or aluminium welding fumes can cause pulmonary fibrosis.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] Fine aluminium powder can ignite or explode, posing another workplace hazard.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] Drinking water contains more aluminium than solid food; however, aluminium in food may be absorbed more than aluminium from water.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] Dietary exposure in Europeans averages to 0.2–1.5 mg/kg/week but can be as high as 2.3 mg/kg/week.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] Higher exposure levels of aluminium are mostly limited to plumbers, masons, electrical workers, machinists, and surgeons.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] Consumption of antacids, antiperspirants, vaccines, and cosmetics provide possible routes of exposure.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] Consumption of acidic foods or liquids with aluminium enhances aluminium absorption, and maltol has been shown to increase the accumulation of aluminium in nerve and bone tissues.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] In case of suspected sudden intake of a large amount of aluminium, the only treatment is deferoxamine mesylate which may be given to help eliminate aluminium from the body by chelation therapy.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] However, this should be applied with caution as this reduces not only aluminium body levels, but also those of other metals such as copper or iron.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] High levels of aluminium occur near mining sites; small amounts of aluminium are released to the environment at coal-fired power plants or incinerators.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] Aluminium in the air is washed out by the rain or normally settles down but small particles of aluminium remain in the air for a long time.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] Acidic precipitation is the main natural factor to mobilize aluminium from natural sources and the main reason for the environmental effects of aluminium; however, the main factor of presence of aluminium in salt and freshwater are the industrial processes that also release aluminium into air.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] In water, aluminium acts as a toxic agent on gill-breathing animals such as fish when the water is acidic, in which aluminium may precipitate on gills, which causes loss of plasma- and hemolymph ions leading to osmoregulatory failure.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] Organic complexes of aluminium may be easily absorbed and interfere with metabolism in mammals and birds, even though this rarely happens in practice.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] Aluminium is primary among the factors that reduce plant growth on acidic soils.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] Although it is generally harmless to plant growth in pH-neutral soils, in acid soils the concentration of toxic Al3+ cations increases and disturbs root growth and function.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] Wheat has developed a tolerance to aluminium, releasing organic compounds that bind to harmful aluminium cations.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] Sorghum is believed to have the same tolerance mechanism.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] Aluminium production possesses its own challenges to the environment on each step of the production process.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] The major challenge is the emission of greenhouse gases.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] These gases result from electrical consumption of the smelters and the byproducts of processing.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] The most potent of these gases are perfluorocarbons, namely CF4 and C2F6, from the smelting process.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] Biodegradation of metallic aluminium is extremely rare; most aluminium-corroding organisms do not directly attack or consume the aluminium, but instead produce corrosive wastes.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] The fungus *Geotrichum candidum* can consume the aluminium in compact discs.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/aluminum-p02] The bacterium *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* and the fungus *Cladosporium resinae* are commonly detected in aircraft fuel tanks that use kerosene-based fuels (not avgas), and laboratory cultures can degrade aluminium.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Some fire-safe polymers naturally exhibit an intrinsic resistance to decomposition, while others are synthesized by incorporating fire-resistant additives and fillers.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Current research in developing fire-safe polymers is focused on modifying various properties of the polymers such as ease of ignition, rate of heat release, and the evolution of smoke and toxic gases.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Standard methods for testing polymer flammability vary among countries; in the United States common fire tests include the UL 94 small-flame test, the ASTM E 84 Steiner Tunnel, and the ASTM E 622 National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) smoke chamber.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Research on developing fire-safe polymers with more desirable properties is concentrated at the University of Massachusetts Amherst and at the Federal Aviation Administration where a long-term research program on developing fire-safe polymers was begun in 1995.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] The Center for UMass/Industry Research on Polymers (CUMIRP) was established in 1980 in Amherst, MA as a concentrated cluster of scientists from both academia and industry for the purpose of polymer science and engineering research.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Controlling the flammability of different materials has been a subject of interest since 450 B.C. when Egyptians attempted to reduce the flammability of wood by soaking it in potassium aluminum sulfate (alum).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Between 450 B.C. and the early 20th century, other materials used to reduce the flammability of different materials included mixtures of alum and vinegar; clay and hair; clay and gypsum; alum, ferrous sulfate, and gypsum; and ammonium chloride, ammonium phosphate, borax, and various acids.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] These early attempts found application in reducing the flammability of wood for military materials, theater curtains, and other textiles, for example.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Important milestones during this early work include the first patent for a mixture for controlling flammability issued to Obadiah Wyld in 1735, and the first scientific exploration of controlling flammability, which was undertaken by Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac in 1821.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Research on fire-retardant polymers was bolstered by the need for new types of synthetic polymers in World War II.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] The combination of a halogenated paraffin and antimony oxide was found to be successful as a fire retardant for canvas tenting.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Synthesis of polymers, such as polyesters, with fire retardant monomers were also developed around this time.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Traditional polymers decompose under heat and produce combustible products; thus, they are able to originate and easily propagate fire (as shown in Figure 1).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] The combustion process begins when heating a polymer yields volatile products.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] If these products are sufficiently concentrated, within the flammability limits, and at a temperature above the ignition temperature, then combustion proceeds.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] As long as the heat supplied to the polymer remains sufficient to sustain its thermal decomposition at a rate exceeding that required to feed the flame, combustion will continue.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] The purpose is to control heat below the critical level.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] To achieve this, one can create an endothermic environment, produce non-combustible products, or add chemicals that would remove fire-propagating radicals (H and OH), to name a few.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] These specific chemicals can be added into the polymer molecules permanently (see Intrinsically Fire-Resistant Polymers) or as additives and fillers (see Flame-Retardant Additives and Fillers).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Oxygen catalyzes the pyrolysis of polymers at low concentration and initiates oxidation at high concentration.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Transition concentrations are different for different polymers.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Additionally, polymers exhibit a structural-dependent relationship with oxygen.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Some structures are intrinsically more sensitive to decomposition upon reaction with oxygen.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] The amount of access that oxygen has to the surface of the polymer also plays a role in polymer combustion.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Oxygen is better able to interact with the polymer before a flame has actually been ignited.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] In most cases, results from a typical heating rate (e.g.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] 10°C/min for mechanical thermal degradation studies) do not differ significantly from those obtained at higher heating rates.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] The extent of reaction can, however, be influenced by the heating rate.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] For example, some reactions may not occur with a low heating rate due to evaporation of the products.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Volatile products are removed more efficiently under low pressure, which means the stability of the polymer might have been compromised.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Decreased pressure also slows down decomposition of high boiling products.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] The polymers that are most efficient at resisting combustion are those that are synthesized as intrinsically fire-resistant.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] However, these types of polymers can be difficult as well as costly to synthesize.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Modifying different properties of the polymers can increase their intrinsic fire-resistance; increasing rigidity or stiffness, the use of polar monomers, and/or hydrogen bonding between the polymer chains can all enhance fire-resistance.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Most intrinsically fire-resistant polymers are made by incorporation of aromatic cycles or heterocycles, which lend rigidity and stability to the polymers.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Polyimides, polybenzoxazoles (PBOs), polybenzimidazoles, and polybenzthiazoles (PBTs) are examples of polymers made with aromatic heterocycles (Figure 2).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Polymers made with aromatic monomers have a tendency to condense into chars upon combustion, decreasing the amount of flammable gas that is released.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Syntheses of these types of polymers generally employ prepolymers which are further reacted to form the fire-resistant polymers.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Ladder polymers are a subclass of polymers made with aromatic cycles or heterocycles.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Ladder polymers generally have one of two types of general structures, as shown in Figure 3.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] One type of ladder polymer links two polymer chains with periodic covalent bonds.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] In another type, the ladder polymer consists of a single chain that is double-stranded.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Both types of ladder polymers exhibit good resistance to decomposition from heat because the chains do not necessarily fall apart if one covalent bond is broken.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] However, this makes the processing of ladder polymers difficult because they are not easily melted.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] These difficulties are compounded because ladder polymers are often highly insoluble.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Inorganic and semiorganic polymers often employ silicon-nitrogen, boron-nitrogen, and phosphorus-nitrogen monomers.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] The non-burning characteristics of the inorganic components of these polymers contribute to their controlled flammability.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] For example, instead of forming toxic, flammable gasses in abundance, polymers prepared with incorporation of cyclotriphosphazene rings give a high char yield upon combustion.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Polysialates (polymers containing frameworks of aluminum, oxygen, and silicon) are another type of inorganic polymer that can be thermally stable up to temperatures of 1300-1400 °C.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Additives are divided into two basic types depending on the interaction of the additive and polymer.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Reactive flame retardants are compounds that are chemically built into the polymer.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Additive flame retardants, on the other hand, are compounds that are not covalently bound to the polymer; the flame retardant and the polymer are just physically mixed together.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Only a few elements are being widely used in this field: aluminum, phosphorus, nitrogen, antimony, chlorine, bromine, and in specific applications magnesium, zinc and carbon.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] One prominent advantage of the flame retardants (FRs) derived from these elements is that they are relatively easy to manufacture.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] They are used in important quantities: in 2013, the world consumption of FRs amounted to around 1.8/2.1 Mio t for 2013 with sales of 4.9/5.2 billion USD.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Market studies estimate FRs demand to rise between 5/7 % pa to 2.4/2.6 Mio t until 2016/2018 with estimated sales of 6.1/7.1 billion USD.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] The most important flame retardants systems used act either in the gas phase where they remove the high energy radicals H and OH from the flame or in the solid phase, where they shield the polymer by forming a charred layer and thus protect the polymer from being attacked by oxygen and heat.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Flame retardants based on bromine or chlorine, as well as a number of phosphorus compounds act chemically in the gas phase and are very efficient.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Others only act in the condensed phase such as metal hydroxides (aluminum trihydrate, or ATH, magnesium hydroxide, or MDH, and boehmite), metal oxides and salts (zinc borate and zinc oxide, zinc hydroxystannate), as well as expandable graphite and some nanocomposites (see below).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Phosphorus and nitrogen compounds are also effective in the condensed phase, and as they also may act in the gas phase, they are quite efficient flame retardants.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Overviews of the main flame retardants families, their mode of action and applications are given in.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Further handbooks on these topics are A good example for a very efficient phosphorus-based flame retardant system acting in the gas and condensed phases is aluminium diethyl phosphinate in conjunction with synergists such as melamine polyphosphate (MPP) and others.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] These phosphinates are mainly used to flame retard polyamides (PA) and polybutylene terephthalate (PBT) for flame retardant applications in electrical engineering/electronics (E&E).
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Besides providing satisfactory mechanical properties and renewability, natural fibers are easier to obtain and much cheaper than man-made materials.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Moreover, they are more environmentally friendly.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Recent research focuses on application of different types of fire retardants during the manufacturing process as well as applications of fire retardants (especially intumescent coatings) at the finishing stage.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Nanocomposites have become a hotspot in the research of fire-safe polymers because of their relatively low cost and high flexibility for multifunctional properties.
[src:fire-safe-polymers/fire-safe-polymers] Gilman and colleagues did the pioneering work by demonstrating the improvement of fire-retardancy by having nanodispersed montmorillonite clay in the polymer matrix.
